<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Divorce Rate at Record High, says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one third of all
marriages in European Union (EU) countries will fail and the
number of marriages is also decreasing, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
One out of four EU marriages is ending in divorce and the rate
is escalating, according to a report published by Eurostat, the
EU's statistical office in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Of Europeans married in 1960, 14 percent have divorced. The
figure rises to 22 percent for those who married in 1970 and 27
percent in 1980, says the report.
</P>
<P>
Marriages are most at risk in Belgium and Sweden where more
than half of all couples will probably divorce. The divorce rate
is also high in Finland with 49 percent, the United Kingdom with
45 percent and Denmark with 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
Italy and other Mediterranean countries have the most stable
marriages; their divorce rates are 10 percent and 20 percent
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
