<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Accounts of HKSARG Land Fund Trust Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Trustees of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region Government (HKSARG) Land Fund
Trust announced here today that the operation of the Land Fund was
normal and good results have been achieved during the 15-month
period ended June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Following the announcement today, the trust will submit its
final accounts to HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa tomorrow and
is to be dissolved on the same day.
</P>
<P>
As of June 30, the net assets of the Land Fund amounted to
197.1 billion HK dollars (25.3 billion U.S. dollars), reflecting
an increase of 85.87 billion HK dollars (11.0 billion U.S.
dollars) or 77 percent over the end of March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The investment surplus for the period was 21.53 billion HK
dollars (2.8 billion U.S. dollars), representing an increment of
84 percent over the accumulated surplus of last year. During the
period, HKSARG's share of land premium income increased by 64.34
billion HK dollars (8.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
As of June 30, the accumulated investment surplus was 47.1
billion HK dollars (6 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Land Fund was handed over by the Central Government to the
chief executive of the HKSAR on July 1 when the HKSARG was
established.
</P>
<P>
The trust was set up in August 1986 for managing HKSARG's share
of land premium income through diversified commercial investment
activities.
</P>
<P>
After over 11 years' prudent management and effective
operation, the net assets of the fund soared from just 772 million
HK dollars (99 million U.S. dollars) to 197.1 billion HK dollars
(25.3 billion U.S. dollars), the chief executive of the trust,
Chung Shui-ming, told a press conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Weathering one after another financial turbulence and keen
competition from the industry, the fund has realized an annual
rate of return of 9.09 percent, one percentage point higher than
the annual inflation rate. "We have been very successful in
achieving satisfactory returns in the past 11 years," Chung said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
