<HEADLINE> EU, ACP Relations Should be More Political: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
official today said that consultations on the future of relations
between the EU and African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries
should be more political and differentiated.
</P>
<P>
Joan de Deus Pinheiro, the EU development commissioner, made
the remark at a two-day conference held in Brussels on the future
of relations between the EU and ACP countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that it seemed necessary to give their relations "a
more marked political dimension by conducting a more effective and
more detailed dialogue on political matters."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to introduce the principle of
differentiation and to support actively the regional integration
efforts in ACP countries.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner announced that on the basis of the
consultations held so far, the European Commission, the EU's
executive arm, would present to the EU member states by November
1997 political guidelines for the future relations with ACP
countries.
</P>
<P>
A convention was signed in 1975 in Lome, capital of the African
country Togo, by 46 ACP countries and the then European Economic
Community to provide financial aid to ACP countries.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between EU and ACP countries should start before
the end of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
