<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Rejects Opposition Call for Wage Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
government today rejected an appeal by main opposition Social
Democrats (SPD) to raise wages in order to boost domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition said an increase in wages would drive up
costs and prices when there was already reluctance to invest in
Germany. They also believed such a move would cause companies to
further reduce their workforce to save money.
</P>
<P>
But SPD leader Oskar Lafontaine said only strengthened
domestic demand could boost the economy and, in turn, create more
jobs and attract more investment.
</P>
<P>
He added wages have hardly been raised in real terms in western
Germany since 1989.
</P>
<P>
"If wages hang too far behind an increase in productivity, this
becomes a burden for domestic demand." 
</P>
</TEXT>
