<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Committee of ITA Hold First Meeting in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The WTO Committee of
Participants on the Expansion of Trade in Information Technology
Products held its first meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
The 43 participants will discuss expansion of product coverage
and reduction of non-tariff barriers. They are to submit their
lists of additional products for inclusion into the Information
Technology Agreement (ITA) between October 1, 1997 and December
31, 1997. They are also to start consultations on divergences in
classifying Information Technology (IT) products.
</P>
<P>
Most of the participants said that they have started the
implementation of the ITA on July 1, 1997, as scheduled in the
agreement reached on March 26. India, Israel and Turkey have
completed domestic ratification and have started implementing the
ITA recently, according to a spokesman of WTO, the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei, which is not yet a WTO member, said it had
started implementing the ITA on an autonomous basis on July 1,
1997. The Czech Republic, Poland, Romania, and the Slovak Republic
said they will implement the agreement after completion of
domestic ratification procedures. The ITA tariff schedules of
Panama, which became a WTO member early this month, and Latvia,
which is negotiating its membership, will have to be verified.
</P>
<P>
The 43 ITA participants are Australia, Canada, Costa Rica, the
Czech Republic, El Salvador, Estonia, the European Community (15
countries), Hong Kong of China, Iceland, India, Indonesia, Israel,
Japan, Korea, Liechtenstein, Macau, Malaysia, New Zealand, Norway,
the Philippines, Poland, Romania, Singapore, the Slovak Republic,
Switzerland, Chinese Taipei, Thailand, Turkey, and the United
States. They share 95 percent of the world trade in information
technology products, which stood at about 600 billion US dollars
in 1995 (correct).
</P>
<P>
The ITA provides for the "staging" of tariff reductions in four
equal rate reductions (25 percent each time): the first cut from
July 1, 1997, the second cut from January 1, 1998, the third cut
from January 1, 1999, and the fourth cut, complete elimination of
duties, from January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of the ITA committee is scheduled on October
30, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
