<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Foreign Currency Reserves in  Unusual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's foreign currency
reserves have drastically dropped to two months import cover in
contrast to the four months usually expected this time of the
year, a banker said today.
</P>
<P>
"This is something new because i think it has never been that
low since 1994, and especially after tobacco exports which
usually boost the reserves," said first banking corporation
official Andy Hodges.
</P>
<P>
It has always been the central bank's target not to go below
four months import cover.
</P>
<P>
As of the end of August the country's foreign currency
reserves had risen to five months import cover since the opening
of the tobacco marketing season in April.
</P>
<P>
Hodges suggested various factors, including the reduction in
tobacco exports or an increase in imports in the run up for
christmas, as possible causes for the drop.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco marketing season ended last week with a total
sales figure of 185 million kg worth five billion Zimbabwe
dollars, after sales had been revised four times during the
auction period due to reduced yields resulting from excessive
rains.
</P>
<P>
Last year 202 million kg exported earned the country in excess
of eight billion Zimbabwe dollars in foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
Currently one U.S. dollar equals to 12 Zimbabwe dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, stockbrokers have noted that the local unit had
been under pressure since the announcement by the reserve bank of
Zimbabwe that the Zimbabwe dollar was about five percent
overvalued in July.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe dollar/U.S. dollar exchange rate will end the
year at around 13 according to stockbrokers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
