<HEADLINE> Chinese Comedy Contest Set to Tickle Funny Bones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to host a
national comic dialogue contest next month to tickle the funny
bones of its people and prove its a nation that does know how to
laugh.
</P>
<P>
The Golden Lion award, the top award in the field of comedy,
will be presented to those jokesters who can make their audience
laugh loudest and longest, organizers told a press conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
In ancient China the comedy routine was one of the favorite
traditional entertainments -- sometimes beating Beijing Opera
hands down. The stage performance is usually given by two people
who are trained to tell funny stories, crack jokes and imitate
various noises.
</P>
<P>
But the popularity of the genre has waned in the 1990s,
overshadowed by trendier entertainments such as Karoake and VCDs.
</P>
<P>
There are currently only 40 professional comedic artists still
performing comic dialogue in China. Many of them are elderly.
</P>
<P>
The contest, organized by the Ministry of Culture and the
Ministry of Radio, Film and Television, is meant to revive the art
form, said a Culture Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Arts departments across the country have been told to organize
writers and performers, especially young people, to get involved
in the fun.
</P>
<P>
But some people said that lack of formal education among the
comic dialogue artists will affect the future of the genre in the
21st century. Mediocre talent and lack of a sharp sense of humor
are the two biggest pitfalls for Chinese comics, the official said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
