<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: France, U.S. Face Confrontation over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- France and the United States
are facing confrontation over a 2 billion U.S. dollar deal signed
by the French oil group Total with Iran, to develop a gas field in
the Gulf, which could expose the French group to U.S. unilateral
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt today
warned the United States against taking rash action against Total,
and reiterated France's rejection of the d'Amato law, which bans
everybody in the world from making oil deal with Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The United States today formally launched an inquire into the
contract announced by Total on Sunday, and a U.S. State Department
spokesman said Washington regrets that Total has signed such a
deal.
</P>
<P>
In association with the Russian oil company Russe Gazprom and
the Malaysian company Petronas, Total will explore with the
National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC) of Iran a giant offshore gas
field in southern Par in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The gas field, which is 70 meters under water and is estimated
to have 8,000 billion cubic meters of gas reserve, will start
producing gas by 2002, according to Total.
</P>
<P>
This contract, which allows Total to have 40 percent of the
shares of a future oil consortium to be produced from the gas
field, also makes the French oil group the first cooperator of
Tehran in hydrocarbon and oil development and trade.
</P>
<P>
This latest action by Total was a defiance of the U.S.
unilateral banning of all oil deals with the Islamic republic,
which it accused of "supporting terrorism" and should be banned
from getting capital to purchase weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Washington institutionalized the unilateral ban by adopting the
d'Amato law in August 1996, which says that the United States will
punish all those -- at home and abroad -- who deal more than 40
million U.S. dollars with Iran and Libya in oil and hydrocarbon
sector, the economic lifeline of the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Washington had expressed its irritation several times over
negotiations held between Total and Iran on oil development, and
said sanctions were likely against the oil group.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions could include a total banning of exports to the
United States of products by the company in question.
</P>
<P>
The law, named after Republican Senator Alfonse d'Amato who
proposed it, has never been applied since being signed by
President Bill Clinton, although Turkey was subjected to U.S.
investigation over its activities in Iranian oil sector last year.
</P>
<P>
France and most European Union countries rejected the law, as
well as its brother law of Helms-Burton Act, which bans foreign
companies from making deals with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"The d'Amato law is America's. So it should be imposed only in
America and upon American companies," said the French foreign
ministry spokesman, "The valid sanctions of international law are
those taken by the United Nations Security Council."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with daily Le Monde published today, the
president of Total Thierry Desmarest said that his company had
obtained approval and support from the French government and
"European authorities" before it signed the deal.
</P>
<P>
A Total spokesman said that the contract signed with Iran does
not "transgress any international rule or law", and pointed out
that there does not exist any internationally recognized organ
which restrains world countries from developing trade relations
with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We working on a contract which conforms with our industrial
criteria as in about 15 other countries," said the spokesman
without specifying which countries these are. He also said that
Total will continue to work from its strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
Total's investment in North America is relatively limited.
</P>
<P>
France and most other European countries have adopted
anti-boycott policy against the United States in case the
Americans impose sanctions upon European companies with unilateral
laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
