<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Rate in US Unchanged Despite Income Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The poverty rate in the
U.S. last year remained about the same as in 1995 although
Americans' real income went up for the second year in a row, the
U.S. Census Bureau said today.
</P>
<P>
An annual report released by the bureau said the number of poor
Americans totaled 36.5 million in 1996, about 13.7 percent of the
nation's population. It compared with 36.4 million and 13.8
percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the poverty threshold for a family of four in the
country was 16,036 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said the overall poverty rate for children in the
the U.S. was 20.5 percent and 10.8 percent for those aged 65 and
over, essentially unchanged.
</P>
<P>
But the number of children under age 18 lacking health
insurance grew quickly to 10.6 million last year from 9.8 million
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
There were no significant changes in 1996 in poverty rates for
whites, blacks, Asians or persons of Hispanic origin.
</P>
<P>
The report said that real median income of U.S. households rose
by 1.2 percent from 35,082 dollars in 1995 to 35,492 dollars last
year. It was the second consecutive annual increase for household
incomes in metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
Before 1995, households in these areas had not had an increase
since 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Cases on Rise in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The number of malaria cases
in Africa has over the past 10 years increased from 100 million
to about 270-480 million, Director of Africa Regional Office
(AFRO) of the World Health Organization (WHO) Ebrahim Samba said
today.
</P>
<P>
His speech was delivered at a three-day malaria control
workshop which started here today to develop detailed plans of
action including advocacy and social mobilization activities
against the disease.
</P>
<P>
Samba said the situation is now being complicated by
increasing malaria epidemics in eastern and southern Africa and
chloroquine resistance in countries such as Malawi, Kenya and
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
He said WHO had adopted a regional malaria control strategy to
reduce social and economic losses caused by malaria.
</P>
<P>
"In response to the decision of the Executive Board to
increase support for malaria control in Africa, WHO made
available nine million U.S. Dollars for accelerated malaria
control in the region in 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
An additional nine million U.S. Dollars will also be made
available in 1998 and 21 additional countries will benefit from
this allocation, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
