<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> R. Korea Attaches Great Importance to Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Korea
welcomed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's reform proposals
designed to enhance the Organization' economic and social
initiatives as well as development activities, its Foreign
Minister Yoo Chong-Ha stressed here today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that his country also welcomed the
adoption of the Agenda for Development at the last session of he
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the fifty-second session of the General Assembly,
Yoo said in this era of inter-dependence among states, the
international community could not remain indifferent to the
under-development of much of the world.
</P>
<P>
He said Korea, now a member of the Organization for Economic
Co-operation and Development(OECD) would participate more
vigorously in South-South cooperation projects with a view to play
a bridging role between the developed and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Yoo said in an effort to expand assistance to the
least-developed countries, Korea has participated in bilateral
cooperation projects with the Economic Commission for Africa(ECA)
since 1995, and planned to undertake a Programme for the
Development of Africa for the period of 1998 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
On environmental issues, the foreign minister said his country
welcomed the adoption of the Programme for Further Implementation
of Agenda 21 at the 19th Special Session of the General Assembly
and stood committed to faithly participating in its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said his country's proposal to conduct a
feasibility study on the transfer of publicly-owned technology was
supported by developed and the developing countries alike, and the
result of the study would be presented at the sixth session of the
Commission on Sustainable Development next year.
</P>
<P>
Through these efforts, the foreign minister hoped to expedite
the transfer of environmentally sound technologies and to promote
international cooperation in environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
