<HEADLINE> Taliban Claim Capture Airport of Rivals' Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between the Afghan
Islamic Taliban militia and their rival forces for the control of
Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 km north of Kabul, was continuing today
amidst claims of success by the both sides, Afghan sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's spokesman Mohammad Haqqani claimed that they had
captured the airport of Mazar-e-Sharif, the stronghold of the
anti-Taliban northern alliance following their three-pronged from
east, west and northern sides of the city, the Afghan sources in
Peshawar, northwest Pakistan, said this evening.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the Taliban's claims, spokesman of the northern
alliance Dr. Talib said that the alliance's forces had repulsed
the militia's strong offensive and caught some of the Taliban's
commanders, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, no independent confirmation of the claims by the both
sides was immediately available.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks, Mazar-e-Sharif has been under the
attack of Taliban, who now control two thirds of the Afghan
territory.
</P>
<P>
The hard-line militia briefly controlled the Mazar-e-Sharif
airport, about 18 km east of the city, early this month, but were
forced to retreat in a few days.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance, which comprises Uzbek warlord Abdul
Malik, Afghanistan's former military chief Ahmad Masood and the
Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat, has been battling the Taliban in western,
northern and central Afghanistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
