<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Americans Support Efforts to Slow Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Most Americans believe
global warming is a serious threat and they are ready to support
international efforts to curb carbon emissions, said a poll
released today by the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, conducted by the Mellman Group, 72
percent of voters would support an international agreement to
reduce carbon emissions by 20 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-six percent of the voters said global warming should be a
priority issue for the U.S. government, and 80 percent respondents
said they would be willing to pay five U.S. dollars a month more
for cleaner energy alternatives such as wind and solar power.
</P>
<P>
The poll was released a week before a White House conference
intended to raise public awareness on the global warming.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton will host a day-long conference on
October 6 to try to build support for his effort to get an
international treaty for countries to reduce their heat-trapping
carbon emissions from burning coal and oil.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government also is in the process of determining the
targets and timetables for reducing emissions it will seek in the
climate change treaty negotiations that are to end in December in
Kyoto, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Job Prospects Forecast to Be Best for 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Employment prospects in
Britain over the next three months will rise dramatically to reach
levels not seen since the late 1980s, according to a leading
employment survey published today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the recruitment company Manpower and
covering more than 2,300 employers, said that 32 percent of firms
surveyed are expecting to increase staff levels in the last
quarter of this year, with only nine percent forecasting a fall
and 58 percent no change.
</P>
<P>
The positive balance of 23 percent marks a six percentage
points increase on the same period last year, and is a rise from
20 percent in the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that service sector firms are leading the way,
with a net balance of 32 percent of service companies forecasting
a rise in jobs, a sharp increase from the 19 percent figure for
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, job prospects for manufacturing is also strong, with
a net balance of 22 percent forecasting to expand their workforce.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey warned that the current figures "parallel
the situation before the economy dipped into recession in 1990".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
