<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Meets Israeli, Arab Foreign Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright met with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
here this morning prior to her scheduled session with
representatives of Israel and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. State Department, Albright has worked
"assiduously" over the last few weeks to restart direct talks
between Israel and Palestine and hopes that her meeting with Levy
and Palestinian negotiator Mahmoud Abbas later today will produce
results.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process came to a standstill in March after
Israel decided to go ahead with Jewish settlement expansion in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a just-released statement, the State Department cautioned
that there is still "a great deal of work to be done in the coming
days and weeks if the promise of peace in the Middle East is to
become a reality".
</P>
<P>
Press reports from Jerusalem said a senior adviser to Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Monday that Israel would consider
handing over additional West bank land only once Palestine has
made "a serious effort " to crack down Islamic militant groups.
</P>
<P>
Albright today had breakfast with the foreign ministers of
Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Oman,
which together with Kuwait form the Gulf Cooperation Council.
</P>
<P>
She has scheduled meetings also with foreign ministers of
Egypt and Jordan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Her meeting with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara also
planned for today is seen as an effort to resume peace talks
between Israel and Syria as the meeting follows her talks with
Levy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Massacres Condemned in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 29 (Xinhua) -- North Mogadishu faction
leader, Ali Mahdi Mohamed, has condemned the forces of Hussein
Mohamed Aidid for committing massacres against the communities of
Rahanwein in the regions of Bay and Bakol of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Radio North Mogadishu quoted Ali Mahdi Mohamed last night as
saying that Hussein Aidid's men are carrying out what he called
genocide and eradication activities against the Rahanwein
communities.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi has called on the United Nations, international and
regional organizations to keep an eye on what's going on in Bay
and Bakol regions of southwestern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
He further said that the consequences of the alleged genocide
will remain in the history of Hussein Aidid's men.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA)
spokesman spoke about mass killings against the innocent
supporters of the RRA in those regions.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle, told the journalists
yesterday afternoon that 19 villages consisting of more than
1,500 houses inhabited by the Rahanwein people were set on fire
by the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said 260 innocent civilians including women and
infants were killed and some of them were burned in their houses
in the past three days in the villages.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle has called on the international community to help the
people in Bay and Bakol regions and send an investigative body to
the area.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, a spokesman for Hussein Aidid's government
described the allegations by the RRA as purely fabricated lies.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Mohamed Qanyare Afrah, said that their forces
in the region sometimes clash with what he called bandits armed
by the Ethiopian government forces in Gedo region.
</P>
<P>
Afrah, Interior Minister of Hussein Aidid, said if there were
any killings, the Ethiopian-manipulated elements of RRA whose aim
is according to him to destabilize the region have carried out.
</P>
<P>
There's no independent confirmation about the opposing
allegations regarding the matter concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
