<HEADLINE> Partnerships in Housing Need Urged at Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, September (Xinhua) - The local Government
Association (LGA), National Housing Federation (NHF) and the
Chartered Institute of Housing have joined forces at the first day
of the Labor Party Conference to get the message across that
partnership matter.
</P>
<P>
The focal point of the conference this year is the vote on the
proposed Partnership in Power reforms, designed to build a
successful partnership between the party and new Labor government.
</P>
<P>
The document Making Partnership Work released here today
recognizes that many successful partnerships exist, but that a
strategic approach to working together is vital if the current
scale of housing need is to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, in 1996 almost 117,000 families were
accepted as homeless by local authorities and nearly 42,500 home
owners had their properties repossessed.
</P>
<P>
The number of new and refurbished homes started for social
renting in 1996/97 was 42,000 - the lowest since 1945 and less
than half the lowest estimates of demand.
</P>
<P>
Government spending on social housing fell by 61 percent
between 1980 and 1997, the biggest cut endured by any public
service.
</P>
<P>
Almost a quarter of the workforce is in part-time employment,
and the figure is set to grow. One in four households has no
member at work and cannot access the private housing market.
</P>
<P>
The three partners, central and local government and registered
social landlords, each have a vital, though different, role to
play, the document concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
