<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Full Employment for the 21th Century", Chancellor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, September 29 (Xinhua) - British Chancellor
Gordon Brown today promised "job for all" and tax refunds to make
work pay for those on low wages.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening day of the Labor Conference, Brown
committed the Labor Government to achieving full employment for
the first time since it came to power last May.
</P>
<P>
"Full employment for the 21th Century," he declared with
confidence.
</P>
<P>
A commentator at the conference said, the pledge is the
centerpiece of the biggest shake-up in the welfare state since the
Forties.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor hinted that everyone who wants a job should be
able to get one with a new low 10p tax rate to be unveiled in next
Spring's Budget.
</P>
<P>
Those on benefits would be forced to train or get work under a
drive to prevent idlers spending life on the sole, he said.
</P>
<P>
A radical tax credit scheme would top up wage packets so people
are better off in even lowpaid jobs instead of unemployed, he
added.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the Chancellor also signaled a new plan to make
Britain fairer by saying helping the less well-off is the
Government's "top priority".
</P>
<P>
"No Labor government can stand by despite all the talk of
ending the hereditary principle in Parliament when in our society
the children of the poorest have poverty and failure thrust upon
them simply because their parents were poor," Brown said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chancellor believed the way to redistribute wealth
is not to pile taxes on the rich but to give the poor the skills
to do better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
