<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia to Punish Illegal Foreign Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia will impose
punishments on foreigners staying illegally in the country
beginning October 16, a high-ranking Saudi official announced
today.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel Aziz said in a
statement today that his country will continue an extensive
campaign against violators of residence regulations and those of
illegal entry, the Saudi Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the campaign will not stop until illegal
foreign residents and those residing with expired visas are
deported.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia urged in early August all foreigners staying
illegally in the kingdom to leave for their home countries
immediately and set October 16 as the deadline. Those who leave
before the deadline would be exempt from imprisonment and fines.
</P>
<P>
After the deadline illegal foreign laborers would face a
two-year imprisonment and a fine of up to 27,000 U.S. dollars,
according to the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Nationals abeting illegal stay would be punished with a
sentence of six months in jail and a fine of 27,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia launched the campaign three years ago to apprehend
those who breach residence laws and deport them to their native
countries. The kingdom deported about 300,000 illegal expatriates
over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry also warned citizens and local
companies against employing violators or assisting them in a way
they could continue their illegal stay.
</P>
<P>
Every year, millions of Muslims from all over the world flocked
into the kingdom to perform Haj pilgrimage, but some continue to
stay illegally after the festival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
