<HEADLINE> Arafat Hopes Palestinian-Israeli-US Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat has expressed hope that the
tripartite Palestinian-Israeli-U.S. meeting in New York today will
have fruitful results.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to newsmen here today, after meeting with
Tunisian President Zeinul Abidine Bin Ali, he said that a meeting was
to take place in New York today under the sponsorship of U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, between Mohamed Abbas (also
known as Alias Abu Mazen), Secretary General of the Executive
Committee of the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO), and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levi.
</P>
<P>
"We hope", he said, "that something new will come out of this
meeting, but at the same time, we believe that the Israeli
government will not authorize its Foreign Minister to take
decisions on important and urgent matters."
</P>
<P>
Arafat went on to say that his talks with President Ali were
important, constructive and positive. They discussed issues
obstructing the peace process. It is the Israeli government, he
said, that is adopting a new stance refusing to implement the
agreements signed in the U.S. White House.
</P>
<P>
These agreements, he stated, are not bilateral but
international, having taken place under the sponsorship of U.S.
President and signed by each of the U.S., Russia, the EU and
Norway, and in the presence of representatives of Japan, Egypt and
Jordan. It is not within the power of Netanyahu or his government
to evade the implementation of these agreements.
</P>
<P>
President Arafat, on the other hand, spelled out the
determination to solve the outstanding issues such as the
redeployment and withdrawal of Israeli troops from the Palestinian
territories according to the agreed timetables.
</P>
<P>
Arafat left Tunis this afternoon, concluding a 24-hour visit to
Tunisia, on his way to Morocco on a similar visit. Arafat had
visited Algeria Sunday before he came to Tunis. 
</P>
