<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planned Teachers' Strike Illegal: Kenyan Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government today
declared teachers' strike set for Wednesday "unlawful" after its
allowances hike offer was rejected by the 24,000-member Kenya
National Union of Teachers (KNUT), the sponsor of the stoppage.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has made all efforts to end the row
over teachers' pay, "it is clear that the stalemate between the
Ministry of Education and KNUT still persists and there is no
sight to any mutual settlement," Minister for Labor and Manpower
Development Philip Masinde told reporters.
</P>
<P>
However, he called on the KNUT to get to the negotiation table
with the government to seek for solutions "amicably." It is
believed that the strike would hurt the ruling Kenya African
National Union in the impending general elections.
</P>
<P>
KNUT Secretary-General Ambrose Adongo dismissed on Friday the
15-to-100 percent rise in allowances announced by the government
on Thursday, vowing that teachers' 200-percent salary increment
demand should be met otherwise the strike is on schedule.
</P>
<P>
In response, the government said that it is not in a position
to adequately remunerate public employees, including teachers,
due to economic pressures and financial constraints.
</P>
<P>
The 200-percent wage increase means that the treasury spends
50 percent of its annual revenue on salaries for teachers alone,
the governmental argued.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, KNUT issued a seven-day strike notice, saying that
teachers of the country would down their tools on October 1 if
their demands were not met by September 30.
</P>
<P>
On September 1, the government announced to raise teachers'
salaries by 10 and 28 percent, which was immediately rejected by
a furious KNUT, describing the move as "an insult."
</P>
<P>
Teachers are among the lowest paid professionals in the
eastern African country, but carry considerable political
influences especially in the countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
