<HEADLINE> US Congress Leaders Paving Way for Stop-gap Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Congressional
leaders were trying to smooth the way for a temporary spending
measure to avoid the government shutdown when fiscal year of 1997
expires at midnight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Congress has sent to President Clinton three of the 13
bills to outline new budgets for the federal departments and
agencies when the new fiscal year begins October 1. But none has
been signed into law as yet. U.S. government agencies could be
forced to shut down temporarily without renewed funding.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress is again resorting to a stopgap spending bill
to extend current funding until lawmakers finish and Clinton signs
the rest of the bills.
</P>
<P>
The interim bill, expected to be rushed through the House of
Representatives and the Senate quickly, give the lawmakers until
October 23 to work on the rest of regular spending bills.
</P>
<P>
Senate Republican leader Tent Lott and Democratic leader Tom
Daschle today expressed a desire for a "clean" stopgap bill free
of controversial riders that could sail through both chambers on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Neither side, especially Republican congressional leaders,
wants a repeat of the tortuous partial government shutdowns during
a fiscal showdown two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The two shutdowns in late 1995 and early 1996 paralyzed
portions of the U.S. government for a record 27 days, resulting in
a torrent of public rage directed mostly at the Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
