<HEADLINE> Kabila Vows Not to Succumb to External Pressures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 29 (Xinhua)-- Laurent Kabila, visiting
president of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) here today
vowed that he will not succumb to external pressures to
democratize quickly in his country.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made by Kabila during a meeting held at the
state house in Lusaka with Zambian president Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, accompanied by several ministers of his government,
arrived here this morning on a three-day visit at the invitation
of Chiluba, which is his first visit abroad since he became
president of the former Zaire after he overthrew the late Mobutu
Sese Seko' regime four months ago.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Kabila confirmed that there has been some
external forces pressuring him to democratize quickly and to
establish a human rights commission of inquiry to probe suspected
masscres of Ruwandan refugees occured in last May.
</P>
<P>
However, speaking through an interpreter, Kabila said that he
will not succumb to such pressures, adding that he sees no reason
why external forces should condemn a three-month old government
while they failed to condemn the dictatorship in the past
decades.
</P>
<P>
Western countries have urged Kabila to establish a democratic
government and hold general elections as soon as possible and
some of them even declared that if Kabila doesn't do so and
refuses to cooperate with a U.N. human rights commission to probe
the massacres, he will risk losing vital aid from the west.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who came to Zambia for diplomatic and spiritual
support, also expressed his willingness to resume the bilateral
cooperation between the two countries which was jeopardized over
the past years.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Chiluba said that DRC has a lot of problems left
behind by the Mobutu regime which needed to be solved before
democratization.
</P>
<P>
"Take every step carefully without rushing until you move
along with all the people in your task to demorcratize," Chiluba
advised.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also pledged Zambia's continued support for DRC in an
effort to rebuild the country's economy and other sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
