<HEADLINE> European Shares End Off Lows on Wall Street's Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all cut their early losses and ended mixed today, helped by the
recovery of the dollar and the rebound into positive ground of
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
British shares on the London market ended on a weak note after
a lackluster session following Friday's record high, but off
lowest levels as the Dow rebounded. The FTSE-100 index seemed to
find solid support at the 5,200 level, ending 6.0 points down at
5,220.30.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the market's bullish sentiment had faded
after the UK government played down talk of a more positive
position toward European economic and monetary union over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, the CAC-40 index closed marginally higher,
up 3.33 points at 2,988.96. A recovery in New York helped to boost
sentiment in Paris as the market managed to reverse earlier
weakness which was triggered by profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German stocks closed 23.49 points higher at
4,104.27 on the DAX-30 index. Dealers said that the market was
cheered by a strong performance on Wall Street Friday and support
was also provided by a firmer dollar. 
</P>
