<HEADLINE> Chinese Firms Active in Nairobi Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The 95th annual Nairobi
International Show, the largest fair in eastern Africa, started
today with vigorous participation of about 20 Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
A total of 65 foreign firms and 250 local firms, together with
governments of Nigeria, Uganda, Germany and India, took part in
the six-day show, which is traditionally treated as the
shop-window of Kenya's agricultural and industrial progresses.
</P>
<P>
Local people were seen crowded in quite a few Chinese firms'
stands, where colorful garments, toys, bedclothes, shoes,
umbrellas, medicines, small-sized machines are on display and
sale, most of them at very competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
Qi Lin Company Ltd, from China's Hebei Province, said it is
expecting a good turnover at the fair. Qi Lin sold goods worth
about 480,000 Shillings (90,000 U.S. Dollars) at the 1996 show
which also lasted six days.
</P>
<P>
"Kenyan people like Chinese goods very much," said a Chinese
saleswoman, who has stayed in the eastern African country for
some two years.
</P>
<P>
However, several Chinese newcomers in Kenya complained that
they are facing difficulties on capacity-limited Kenyan market
and some of their goods are hard to be sold due to unsuitable
prices and different consuming habits.
</P>
<P>
Chinese products have enjoyed strong performence in the annual
show since 1980s.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, private firms from Israel, the U.S., Iran#,
Syria and Australia are exhibiting at the fair.
</P>
<P>
The number of local firms and foreign governments entering
the 1996 show stood at 236 and eight respectively. 
</P>
