<HEADLINE> US to Enforce Iran Sanctions Law Against France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that it would enforce its tough Iran sanctions law over a
new deal between Tehran and the French oil company Total.
</P>
<P>
The United States applies the sanctions law, approved last
year, because "such investments make more resources available for
Iran to use in supporting terrorism and pursuing missiles and
nuclear weapons," State Department spokesman Christopher Bush told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Washington made the threat after Iran signed a contract Sunday
with a consortium of French, Russian and Malaysian oil companies
to expand the South Pars gas field estimated to hold 300 trillion
cubic feet of gas. The field is in the Persian Gulf adjacent to
Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The companies are Total, a French oil giant with 40 percent
participation in the deal, and Gazprom of Russia and Petronas of
Malaysia, with 30 percent each.
</P>
<P>
The gas contract worth 2 billion dollars goes against the 1996
Iran-Libya sanctions law which requires President Bill Clinton to
penalize any foreign company investing 20 million dollars or more
in the gas and oil sectors of these two countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Senator Alfonse D'Amato, the architect of the Iran-Libya
sanctions law, said Total and its consortium partners should be
sanctioned "to the fullest extent of the law."
</P>
<P>
"This law is a vital weapon for cutting the flow of hard
currency to Iran," he said.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, challenging U.S.
enforcement of the law, said today that the United States had no
right to impose sanction on the French company Total for the gas
contract with Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said France's European Union partners backed Paris's view on
trade with Iran. "All of the EU is solidly behind our position."
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said
France and its European partners had consistently opposed what
they saw as an attempt by the United States to extend its laws
beyond its border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
