<HEADLINE> Labor Must Never Let Divisions Happen Again: Sawyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Delegates at the
Labor Party Annual Conference today were urged to learn from the
past and looked into the future.
</P>
<P>
Opening the Partnership Into Power debate at the conference,
Tom Sawyer, general secretary of the party, said that in the past
"we haven't always been united."
</P>
<P>
"When we have divided we have lost the peoples trust," he said.
"You all know what happens when parties lose the trust of people.
They get punished at the ballot box."
</P>
<P>
"We have been punished and we have never had two terms of
office," Sawyer added.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the past, Sawyer said that after every single term,
the divisions in one form or another had opened up between the
party and the government.
</P>
<P>
The result was that Labor lost in elections. He said, "We must
never let that happen again."
</P>
<P>
So there is a "health warning" against almost two decades of
Labor's opposition. "That is why what we are putting right today
we are asking you to add the missing links," Sawyer added.
</P>
<P>
Having learned from the past, Sawyer said the Party must find
ways of working which would build the party up rather than weigh
it down.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the goal of Partnership in Power "is to
create ways of working which promote partnership and not hinder
it".
</P>
<P>
This would be the "foundation for another Labor victory and
another," he said. 
</P>
