<HEADLINE> US Approves First Combination AIDS Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Food and Drug
Administration (FDA) has approved the first popular AIDS drugs --
Glaxo Wellcome's Combivir consisting of both the oldest anti-HIV
drug, AZT, and lamivudine.
</P>
<P>
People infected with HIV now have to take more than a dozen
pills a day, at regimented times. Many complain that the schedule
is hard to stick to.
</P>
<P>
"Combining these two drugs, which are commonly prescribed with
one another, into one tablet could decrease the number of pills
people with HIV have to take daily," the FDA said in a statement
today.
</P>
<P>
The Combivir pill contains 300 milligrams of AZT, sold as
Retrovir, and 150 milligrams of lamivudine, sold as Epivir.
</P>
<P>
The FDA said that Combivir had the adverse side effects as the
two drugs used alone -- nausea, diarrhea, anemia, low white blood
cell count and effects on the pancreas and nerves in the hands and
feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
