<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICE Sets Guidelines for Industrial Sub-Contracting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-sized
enterprises finally got something to more than protect themselves
with as the Union of Industrial and Employers' Confederations of
Europe (UNICE) today published guidelines for industrial
sub-contracting.
</P>
<P>
UNICE Secretary General Zygmunt Tyszkiewicz described
application of the guidelines, developed in conjunction with the
European Commission, as contribution to increasing the
competitiveness of all European enterprises, especially SMEs, the
initials for small and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines, first proposed in 1994 and formulated by
purchasers and suppliers representing more than 15 million
European companies large and small, are intended to establish the
basic principles and recommended framework for partnership between
parties throughout the supply chain.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines outline "best practice" for terms of payment,
quality and industrial property rights and also serve as a
reference for parties negotiating sub-contracting or specific
sectoral agreements.
</P>
<P>
"The essence of partnering is cooperation between a supplier
and a purchaser for mutual benefit," said the UNICE secretary
general who termed the guidelines as a set of self-regulation
rather than legislation.
</P>
<P>
Both the supplier and the purchaser can benefit from their
cooperation if they both respect the guidelines and there does not
have to have a winner and a loser in business dealings,
Tyszkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
Late payment has been a headache for SMEs in their past
dealings with large companies whereas the UNICE guidelines
stipulate that contractual terms of payment should contain a
clause whereby the supplier is automatically entitled to interest
at an agreed rate if the purchaser fails to pay the correct amount
on time.
</P>
<P>
The SMEs, employing less than 250 people by UNICE standard,
account for 97.3 percent of the more than 15 million companies now
active in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Home Sales in US Decline Sharply in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- New home sales in the U.S.
fell by 2.2 percent in August resulting from sharp declines in the
West and Midwest, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the single-family homes sold at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 800,000, down from 818,000 in
July.
</P>
<P>
Still, the sales in August marked the 20th consecutive month of
sales above the 700,000 level, the longest such string since late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales of new homes in the month fell by 12.6
percent in the West following an 11.3 percent jump in July. Sales
also fell 4.5 percent in the Midwest. They rose by 3.1 percent in
the South and soared 15.6 percent in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
During the first eight months of the year, sales of new homes
in the country are running 6 percent ahead of the same period of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that supply of new homes for sale --
284,000 in August -- was the slimmest in four years and enough to
last just 4.4 months at the current sales rate.
</P>
<P>
It's the eighth consecutive month of a supply of less than five
months, the longest stretch since 1971.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Economists said strong income, lower mortgage rates and
job growth have made U.S. buyers confident that they can handle
mortgage payments for new hoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
