<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Senior Official on Economic Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy prime
minister Anwar Ibrahim said today that Malaysia's economic growth
next year would be less than the projected 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth for 1998 would not be less than 6.0
percent, but less than the projected 8 percent, Anwar, who is also
the finance minister, told editors of local news organizations at
a briefing here today, according to the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"We will be comfortable with a growth of 7 to 7.5 percent, but
even if we reduce growth to 7 percent, we can still achieve full
employment, given that there have been no reports of major
bankruptcies, closures or lay-offs," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economic growth this year, according to Anwar's
prediction a few weeks ago, would be 8.0 percent. The country had
a growth of 8.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the 1998 Budget would be used as a barometer to
gauge the government's fiscal discipline in tackling the country's
current macroeconomic problems and added that in addition to
recent measures to reduce the current account deficit, such as
deferring major infrastructure projects, the budget would aim at a
more sustainable long term strategy to maintain the nation's
economic stability.
</P>
<P>
He issued a directive to all government bodies, including state
governments and statutory bodies (including self-financed
agencies) to cut down on their spending with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also directed that proposed overseas trade missions be
canceled with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
These new measures are in addition to a recent move to cut
government expenditure by two percent.
</P>
<P>
"The Budget will be reflective of the government's total
commitment to manage our economy prudently," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the lessons learnt from the recent speculative attacks
against the Malaysian ringgit, Anwar said that given time,
Malaysia would be able to recover from the doldrums following
recent efforts to improve the current account deficit, such as
cutting down imports of lumpy items, and deferment of some major
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit has fallen over the past two months from about 2.52
against the U.S. dollar to 3.2405/55 at today's close, a fall of
more than 20 per cent against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange has also dropped by about 40
per cent in terms of market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader said, "The depreciation of the ringgit and
bearish sentiment on the stock market do not reflect our economic
strength or fundamentals, but I am hopeful that given time, the
situation can improve."
</P>
<P>
He did believe that raising interest rates would be a solution
to the problem, saying, "The last option is to leave it to market
forces. They may not be always rational, but this is a temporary
measure."
</P>
<P>
Anwar assured that Malaysia's economy was strong and stressed
that his government would resist any attempts to disrupt the
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
