<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Unique Character" Acceptable to Quebecers, Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Most people in the Canadian
province of Quebec think recognition of the province's "unique
character" is as good or better than being certified as a
"distinct society", a new poll suggests.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it is still not enough for them to accept the Canadian
constitution, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of Quebecers say the September 14
declaration by nine of Canada's 10 provincial leaders that
Quebec's "unique character" should be protected is as good as the
"distinct society" recognition.
</P>
<P>
Another eight percent of those surveyed say the newly-coined
phrase offered more than the old one, which was proposed in the
failed Meech Lake and Charlottetown constitutional reform
packages.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four percent say that "unique character" offered less
than "distinct society", while 14 percent didn't know or didn't
respond.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 44 percent of Quebecers don't consider the new
recognition enough to make them accept the 1982 constitution,
which was patriated from Britain under the Trudeau government and
was never endorsed by Quebec.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted by the Leger and Leger firm from
September 18 to 23 among 1,002 Quebec voters, and is considered
accurate to 3.1 percentage points, 19 times out of 20.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found continuing majority support for Canadian
unity among Quebec voters.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three percent of the voters say they would vote "No" in a
referendum on Quebec sovereignty, while 46 percent would vote
"Yes". 
</P>
</TEXT>
