<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official on Government Role in Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The role of Hong Kong
government in achieving economic growth is "to create a
business-friendly environment for business to flourish", a Hong
Kong senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Trade and Industry Denise Yue made the remark
when officiating at the opening of the Business License
Information Center (BLIC), which is established as part of the
government's effort to help business.
</P>
<P>
Outlining unbroken economic growth for Hong Kong over the past
three decades, Yue said, "while we have every reason to be proud
of our economic achievements, the government does not lay claim to
be the maker of the success."
</P>
<P>
The task of the government is "not to direct development and
usurp the role of businessmen in making business decisions,
breathing down their neck on what they should or should not do,"
she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Our task, first and foremost, is to create a business-friendly
environment for business to flourish, for businessmen to maximize
their entrepreneurial talent," Yue said.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang in his 1996 budget speech
reiterated the government's determination to become as
business-friendly as possible by the introduction of the Helping
Business Program, which focuses on cutting government red-tape,
streamlining regulatory activities and improving public services
to the business sector.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the BLIC is a direct and practical way to
helping our business," Yue said.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, there are 450 different licenses and permits that
are related to business operations of all kinds. These licenses
and permits are administered by 36 different bureaus, departments
and agencies. Some of the licensing requirements cut across
several licensing authorities.
</P>
<P>
With the establishment of the BLIC, businessmen can now look to
a single agent who can give advice on the full range of licensing
requirements for the business they intend to set up, the secretary
said.
</P>
<P>
The center will be particularly useful to small and
medium-sized enterprises which make up the vast majority of the
business community and often cannot afford the service of
business advisers and lack the means to identify licensing
requirements, she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
