<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Delegation Ends China Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A delegation from the United
Nations World Food Program (UNWFP) has ended its week-long visit
to China to inspect WFP-funded projects in Qinghai and Gansu
provinces, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Some of the delegation members left here today for the People's
Democratic Republic of Korea (DPRK) to see the effects of famine
in areas hit by natural disasters. Other delegates are returning
home or to Rome, where WFP headquarters is based.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegates talked with officials from
the Ministry of Agriculture (MOA) and local governments in the
areas which received project funding.
</P>
<P>
The delegates said they are satisfied with the results of the
WFP projects completed in Huangzhong County of Qinghai, and
Jingtai and Gulang counties in Gansu. They also visited Ping'an
and Hualong counties in Qinghai, where a new WFP-funded project is
to be initiated soon.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Jacques Graisse, executive director of the delegation,
told Xinhua that the China tour has left a lasting impression on
all the delegates, and they have been deeply moved by the great
efforts made by the Chinese people and government in
poverty-eradication.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The purpose of this visit is to let the donors, such
as the United States, Canada, Australia and the Republic of Korea
(ROK), see for themselves the effects of WFP-funded projects in China,
and to have a better understanding of the real situation in
China's poor areas."
</P>
<P>
WFP-funded projects in China are the largest in terms of scale
and benefits, compared with those in other developing countries,
he said, noting that China can be a model for implementing similar
projects in other countries.
</P>
<P>
According to MOA officials, since 1979, WFP has agreed to give
food aid to 59 projects in China, valued at 768 million US
dollars. Of these, 48 have been completed, nine are underway and
one is to be launched.
</P>
<P>
Over 22.3 million people in 184 Chinese cities and counties
have benefited from WFP's work.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China still had 58 million people in
absolute poverty, most of whom live in mountainous areas or
ethnic minority regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
