<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Oppositions to Continue Joint Candidacy Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Two major opposition parties in
South Korea announced today that they will extend their
months-long talks on a single candidacy to produce definite
results.
</P>
<P>
The talks were scheduled to be completed by the end of
this month (September).
</P>
<P>
"We have earnestly negotiated fielding a single opposition
candidate in December's presidential election," said a statement
issued by the parties on the last day of the scheduled negotiations.
"But now we need more time," it said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties, the United Liberal Democrats (ULD) and
the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP), however, failed to
decide how long they will extend their talks. They will meet again
possibly Thursday to define the extension period.
</P>
<P>
The extension was decided after it was discovered that Kim
Jong-pil, leader of the second largest opposition ULD, was suffering
from loss of popularity among the five declared presidential
contenders. His counterpart, Kim Dae-jung of the main opposition
NCNP, is leading the popularity polls.
</P>
<P>
Through the negotiations, the two parties are reported to have
agreed on a way to share power in the event either one of them
wins in the December 18 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The parties are also reportedly pushing for a constitutional change
in favor of a parliamentary government system as a campaign pledge.
</P>
<P>
But no progress has clearly been made in talks about who to put
forward between the two Kims as the opposition's joint candidate in
the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The two veteran politicians, both in their early 70s, have said
the coming election is their last chance for a presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP claimed the two parties almost agreed to field Kim
Dae-jung as the opposition's choice in the election, while
promising Kim Jong-pil with strengthened premiership under the
proposed parliamentary government system.
</P>
<P>
But the ULD dismissed the claim, saying nothing has yet been agreed
concerning the single candidacy.
</P>
<P>
ULD leader Kim Jong-pil hinted that he may break the
partnership with the NCNP and run in the election separately.
</P>
<P>
He has recently ordered his party to form a party presidential
election committee to prepare his own campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
