<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Hoi-chang Takes Over Ruling Party Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Presidential candidate lee
Hoi-chang of South Korea's ruling New Korea Party (NKP) was
elected president of the party at its national convention today.
</P>
<P>
Lee, a former Supreme Court judge, joined the NKP early last
year before the April parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of power in the NKP is expected to boost the
political status of candidate Lee, who is suffering a loss of
popularity among the people due to allegations that his two sons
intentionally lost weight to evade military service.
</P>
<P>
To enhance party unity, representative Lee Han-dong, leader of
the party's conservative Minjong faction, who lost the party
presidential nomination to Lee in July, was named party chairman,
the number two post in the NKP.
</P>
<P>
However, it remains to be seen if Lee will successfully promote
party harmony after his election. A group of his opponents
reportedly plan to leave the party in support of former Kyonggi
governor Rhee In-je, who left the party to join the presidential
race on his own.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, reports claim that several members of the party's
largest Minju faction who supported Lee's rivals in the July
nomination race are also considering quitting the party, unless Lee
succeeds in improving his ratings by next month.
</P>
<P>
At today's convention, Lee strongly warned his opponents in the
party against any moves harming party unity.
</P>
<P>
"With the presidential election only 80 days away, the party
has not been gearing up for the vote, or facing the challenges
from outside and inside," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Kim, who maintains his links with the ruling party as
honorary party president, urged party members to rally behind Lee
in the December presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party has been embroiled in a huge intra-party feud
since Lee was elected as its standard-bearer. Citing Lee's falling
popularity ratings, his opponents are exerting pressure on him to
withdraw from the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Recent public surveys show Lee's approval rating as ranking
third, far below front-running Kim Dae-jung of main opposition
National Congress for New Politics, a veteran opposition leader,
and the 49-year-old Rhee.
</P>
<P>
Today's Taegu event marks the first time that a ruling party
has held a national convention in a provincial city.
</P>
<P>
Political observers interpret the move as a wooing gesture to
voters of Taegu and North Kyongsang Province, an area where none
of the five presidential candidates were born. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Police Urged to Cooperate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Police in the 14-member
Southern African Development Community (SADC) should strengthen
their cooperation in the fight against crime if the region is to
be successfully integrated, a Zimbabwean minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa said efforts toward
regional integration in economic and other spheres would fail in
an environment where cross border crime and related activities
have been rife.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing delegates to a Southern African Regional
Police Chiefs Cooperation (sarpcco) extraordinary meeting in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
''Sarpcco, therefore, provides the pillar on which the success
of all other forms of integration rest as we all look forward to
take full advantage and maximize the benefits of the existing
peace within the region,'' said Dabengwa.
</P>
<P>
The fruits of cooperation in the fight against cross border
crime, the minister noted, were beginning to be seen.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,576 stolen vehicles were recovered during the
first phase of Voyager Four operation, an exercise aimed at
dealing with cross border vehicle thefts.
</P>
<P>
A total of 143 car theft suspects were arrested under the
operation which involved Mozambique, South Africa, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
