<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Criticism of China's Birth Control Misplaced: Former PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States' criticism
of China's family planning policy and its efforts to influence the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations' policies towards Burma and
Cambodia are misplaced, Australian former Prime Minister Malcolm
Fraser said today.
</P>
<P>
"These countries are not going to be told by the United States
what they ought to do and why they should do what the United
States says," the former prime minister said at a luncheon in
Melbourne today.
</P>
<P>
China's family planning policy is effective; it has stopped a
potential 90 million births a year, the Australian Associated
Press said in a report on Fraser's speech.
</P>
<P>
"Good relationships are a process of consultations and cooperation.
It's not a process of one large country telling other countries how
they ought to perform, how they ought to behave," said Fraser, who
was Australia's prime minister during 1975-1983.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the United States to stop trying to dictate
to Asia over human rights and to give China greater recognition as
a major economic power.
</P>
<P>
Fraser said the United States should stop blocking China's
entry to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"As the Chinese economy grows, China is going to have a
great effect on raw material prices, raw material supplies ... on
trade and on markets worldwide," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China should be a member of all the world's major economic
institutions, I believe, as quickly as possible," the former prime
minister added.
</P>
<P>
Fraser stressed that Australia's future lay with Asia, saying
the country will be a better one with multi-cultures flourishing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
