<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bridges on Yangtze Play Pivot Role in China's National Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- On average, a new bridge was
thrown across the Yangtze River, the longest in China, in each of
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
These new bridges have made the river belt the most dynamic
economic powerhouse in China.
</P>
<P>
At present, a cross-river highway-railway bridge is being built
in Wuhu of east China's Anhui Province. It is expected to cut
short the length between Xiamen Special Economic Zone in southeast
China's province of Fujian and the Chinese capital of Beijing by
800 km, serving as a link between northern and southern China.
Upon completion in 2000, it is to become a pivot of communications.
</P>
<P>
China has built five bridges on the Yangtze River with a total
investment of 10 billion yuan since the country launched a
campaign to boost economic development along the Yangtze five
years ago, said an official with the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Three other cross-river bridges, being built at Jiangyin,
Nanjing and Chongqing cities, will open to traffic in the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
The official revealed that the number of bridges under
construction or to be planned on the Yangtze River will be
increased to 36, and this is something unprecedented in the world.
</P>
<P>
Along with the bridge building boom, more harbors have emerged
along the section of the Yangtze between Shanghai and Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
The past five years have seen construction of 100 new harbors,
and 16 of them are opened to foreign ships.
</P>
<P>
With improvement of infrastructure, the gross domestic product
(GDP) of eight riverside cities with Pudong New Area as a
pacesetter grew at an annual average of 15 percent in recent
years, much higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Economists agreed that areas along the Yangtze River will be
the economic stars in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth of Jiangxi, Anhui and Hubei, which enjoy
favorable geological positions, were among the fastest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Jiujiang Bridge, which strides over the middle reaches of
the Yangtze and opened to traffic In 1993, serves as an important
link on the Beijing-Kowloon Railway trunk line.
</P>
<P>
The new bridges have helped speed up construction of state key
projects. Xiling Bridge handles 50,000 tons of building materials
a day for the Three Gorges Project which is underway and is
believed the largest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
Though the history of bridge building dated back to ancient
times, China lagged behind other countries in contemporary age
until 1957 when it built its first bridge on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The second bridge, with a span of 6,772 meters, was completed
in 1968 in Nanjing, setting a world record. Before long, a
much longer one which has a 10,497-meter-long railway and a
5,647-meter-long highway, was built in Wuhu, becoming the world's
longest.
</P>
<P>
Some bridges were built with funds raised by non-governmental
organizations and even by farmers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Electoral Commission Chief Outlines His Body's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Justice Woo Kwok-hing,
Chairman of the Electoral Affairs Commission of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), which was established on
Monday, outlined here this evening the priorities for his body in
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
The commission, an independent body, will oversee practical
arrangement for the elections of the first SAR Legislative Council
scheduled to take place in May 1998, Woo said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the commission is responsible for making
recommendations on geographical constituency boundaries and for
the conduct and supervision of the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
It will also supervise the registration of electors and make
arrangements to ensure that the elections are conducted openly,
fairly and honestly, Woo added.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the commission had held its first
meeting this morning to fix the priorities and to discuss how to
accomplish all its tasks as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The first priority for the commission is to finish the division
of the constituency boundaries by the end of October and submit
its recommendations to the SAR's Executive Chief Tung Chee Hwa
afterwards, Woo said.
</P>
<P>
He said the second priority in the commission's work is to work
out regulations over the voter registration and other election
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary for Home Affairs of the SAR government, David
Lan, urged eligible voters on Monday to show their support for the
forthcoming legislative elections by registering themselves.
</P>
<P>
The voter registration work is scheduled to be launched at the
end of this year, Lan said.
</P>
<P>
At today's news conference, Woo also said that only permanent
residents of the SAR enjoy the right to vote or the right to stand
for election.
</P>
<P>
Woo was appointed Chairman of the three-member commission by
the SAR Executive Chief, Tung, in accordance with related laws.
</P>
<P>
As a judge of the Court of First Instance of Hong Kong's High
Court, Woo joined the Bench in 1992 after years of private
practice as a barrister. He was Chairman of the former Boundary
and Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
Two other members of the commission are Norman Leung Nai-pang
and Elizabeth SC Shing.
</P>
<P>
Norman Leung is the Deputy-chairman of the City Bus Group
Limited. He has been involved in a wide range of public Service
and was also a member of the former Boundary and Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Elizabeth Shing is the Director General of the Hong Kong
Management Association. She has extensive experience in the
management field and has served in various advisory institutions.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
