<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Offer Escape Route to Northern Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
forces battling for control of the northern opposition stronghold
of Mazar-i-Sharif have offered enemy fighters an unhindered escape
from the city, said reports monitored here today.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's information minister Amir Muttaqi said the besieging
army had deliberately left open the southern exit of
Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of the Afghan capital of
Kabul, to facilitate a peaceful takeover, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to further tighten our net so the opposition are
compelled to leave," Muttaqi was quoted as saying in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Late Monday Taliban forces were reported to be a mere five km
to the east of the city and the sound of light machine gun fire
was also audible to the north and west.
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi asserted that Taliban fighters were now "digging in" in
their current positions, although he could not give exact details
on the location.
</P>
<P>
He said the gains were made following a massive late-Monday
afternoon Taliban attack on the opposition's seat of shadow
government, and the forces were now attempting to make "gradual
advances."
</P>
<P>
However no independent information was immediately available on
Tuesday's military developments in Mazar-e-Sharif, which is also
the only Afghan city not held by the hard-line militia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
