<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Gains Increasing Popularity in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- American pop music superstar
Mariah Carey recently discussed her life and work in an interview
with a prestigious Beijing newspaper.
</P>
<P>
But unlike its conventional practice, the interview was
conducted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
More and more Chinese people are buying Internet access, which
has given a great number of Chinese PC users more computer options
and introduced them to the joy of traveling on the Information
superhighway.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to listing on the Internet, the Little Swan Corporation,
a namebrand washing machine producer in Wuxi city, east China, had
its output value increased by one fifth in the first half of this
year and invited two foreigners to be its deputy general manager
and assistant to the general manager.
</P>
<P>
Internet was introduced to China in April 1994. A month later,
a domestic system was opened, providing four categories of
service, including science and technology, education and
communications for 150,000 clients.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 100 various kinds of non-governmental
computer service centers have sprung up across the country to
help Chinese PC owners onto the net.
</P>
<P>
The domestic system has been diversified to meet growing
needs. A program to exchange information on the supply and demand
for idle equipment and means of production was launched in June
this year by the Ministry of Internal Trade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Agriculture has opened a network
featuring information on flower trade. Other networks in operation
cover tourism, family teaching and food sales.
</P>
<P>
Last June, China opened the first anti-cancer club on Internet,
by which, cancer patients can obtain advice from specialists, and
exchange views on treatment.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, only 150,000 PC users in China have been connected
with the Internet. The figure in other parts of Asia was as high
as three million, said Zou Xiangqun, deputy secretary-general of
the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
He believes that there is a great potential for computer
network development in China in the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
