<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Says Government Has No Role in Total's Iran Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The French government has
played no role in the signing of a 2 billion U.S. dollar gas
contract between the oil company Total and Iran, French Foreign
Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said today.
</P>
<P>
Calling the Total contract with Iran "purely commercial and not
political," Rummelhardt said the French government "neither
approves it, nor authorizes it, nor stops it.
</P>
<P>
"Total is free to sign this contract, as long as it respects
French and international laws," he added.
</P>
<P>
This is an apparently softening of tone by Paris after Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin severely criticized the U.S. for trying to
impose its domestic laws upon other countries.
</P>
<P>
The negotiation between Total and Iran on signing oil deals was
raised by U.S. State Secretary Madeleine Albright when she met
with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine in New York on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Ambassador to France Felix Rohatyn also reportedly
lodged a protest with the French Foreign Ministry last week for
Total's decision to sign the contract.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said it is considering imposing sanctions on Total for
its violation of the U.S. Iran-Libya sanctions act, also called
the D'Amato Act.
</P>
<P>
The act bans all companies throughout the world from investing
more than 40 million dollars in the oil and hydrocarbon sector of
Iran and Libya, which Washington has accused of backing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac avoided commenting on the U.S.
threat to impose sanctions on Total because it was a contract
signed by a private company, said members of the presidential
staff.
</P>
<P>
The staff members added that Chirac has repeatedly expressed
his disapproval of the D'Amato Act, which he considers
"non-conforming to international law."
</P>
<P>
In Washington, Christopher Bush, a State Department spokesman,
said on Monday that the U.S. intended to apply the D'Amato law
fully.
</P>
<P>
"Our position on any investments in Iranian gas and oil fields
is clear: Such investment makes more resources available for Iran
to use in supporting terrorism and pursuing missiles and nuclear
weapons," said the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft's Chinese, English Products Developed at Same Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The end of September
witnessed the simultaneous launching of the Chinese and English
versions of Microsoft's latest Internet browser, Internet Explorer
4.0 (IE 4.0), in Beijing and San Francisco in the US state of
California.
</P>
<P>
This ended the trend of Chinese-made versions of the world's
leading software producer appearing later than the
English-versions.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony today, Duh Jia-Bin, president of Microsoft
(China) Co., Ltd, said Microsoft has all along been seeking to
speed up the development of the Chinese version of its software.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, from Windows 3.1 to today's Internet
Explorer 4.0, the time lag between the launch of Chinese and
English versions has rapidly decreased from two years. And the
majority of the development work of the Chinese version of IE 4.0
was done in China.
</P>
<P>
"IE 4.0 integrates the personal computer and the Internet,"
making it easy for users to search for information either on their
PC or the Internet, Duh said, adding that "this is an expansion of
Microsoft's concept `Imformation at Your Fingertips.'"
</P>
<P>
Seven major Web sites, such as Data Communication Bureau,
People's Daily and China Economic Information, have been
pre-installed as Active Channels in Chinese IE 4.0 and are just
one click away for users.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Microsoft has more than 300 authorized sales agents,
and has a direct technological support relationship with 30-plus
software developers, and 30-plus central government organs and
banks.
</P>
<P>
Duh said he believes the expansion of Microsoft's China
business demonstrates its confidence in the country's huge market
potential and rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Bill Gates, Microsoft president and CEO, has paid four visits
to China in the past two and a half years. Beijing receives a
visiting vice-president from the Microsoft headquarters every
month on average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0109 </DOCNO>
