<HEADLINE> Philippine President Signs Anti-rape Bill Into Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today signed long-delayed anti-rape bill into law which
redefines rape as a crime against persons and no longer as a crime
against chastity.
</P>
<P>
Ramos described the new law as "a strong confirmation of the
continuing commitment of the Legislative and of the Executive to
pursue social reforms to benefit our disadvantaged sectors."
</P>
<P>
The signing into law of the anti-rape bill is a culmination of
over seven years of legislative work, with the active
participation of organized women's groups.
</P>
<P>
Under the old laws, rape was viewed as a forced assertion of
male dominance over women, and the crime was associated with the
subordination of women to men in the society.
</P>
<P>
With the reclassification of rape as a crime against persons,
the government and its instruments of justice can now file and
pursue a rape case on their own, unlike before when usually only
the victim herself or her next of kin could file a case.
</P>
<P>
To comprehend the full significance of the new law is to
understand the added suffering imposed upon the rape victims who
bear the burden and shame of having to prove that they are not
willing parties to the crime, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the shame felt by so many victims," he said, "they
usually chose to remain silent rather than be further dishonored
during tedious and well-publicized investigations."
</P>
<P>
The new law also recognizes that rape and other social ills
will be reduced only if other preventive and corrective measures
are put in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao Meets with Hong Kong Young People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese leader Hu Jintao met
today with a team of 328 Hong Kong young people who came here to
celebrate the 48th founding anniversary of the People's Republic
of China.
</P>
<P>
Hu, member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of
the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, warmly
welcomed the guests. He told them that the smooth return of
Hong Kong to the motherland signaled the great success of "One
Country, Two Systems" concept set by Deng Xiaoping, and it was an
important step toward the reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the principles of "One Country, Two Systems,"
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high degree of
autonomy in Hong Kong have been implemented earnestly, and the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region is
operating extremely well.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has seen the continuation of prosperity and
stability and we are full of confidence in Hong Kong's future," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hu explained the gist of the 15th National Congress of the CPC
to the young people, saying that one of the important aspects of
holding high the great banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory is to
continue to forge ahead the reunification course based on the "One
Country, Two Systems" concept.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Hong Kong's future and development will depend on
the younger generation. Therefore, Hong Kong's young people should
continue to love the motherland and Hong Kong to make more
contributions to the long-term prosperity and stability of the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
