<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor, who just concluded a two-day tour to Nigeria on Sunday,
is now in Tripoli on a state visit to strengthen bilateral ties
between his country and Libya.
</P>
<P>
A Libyan News Agency report reaching here today said Taylor
was warmly received by Moumar Gaddafi after he travelled by
land transport from Tunisia due to the United Nations embargo.
</P>
<P>
Taylor reportedly has good relations with Gaddafi. The former
key warlord launched the seven-year Liberian civil war in
December 1989, backed by the National Patriotic Front, some of
whose members were trained in Libya.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Taylor has been warned by the United
States that efforts to revive his Libyan connection could harm
the already cordial U.S.-Liberian relations.
</P>
<P>
Taylor was elected as President of Liberia in July this year
at the end of the civil war and his National Patriotic Front party
takes a majority of seats in the new parliament.  
</P>
