<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Sapped by Portfolio Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished lower today after a volatile afternoon triggered by
portfolio-juggling among fund managers.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries finished 7.7 points lower at 2766.9, having
earlier swung between a low of 2754.6 and a high of 2786.0.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index slipped 26.5 points to 4551.8, while
the all resources index gained 8.6 points to 1362.2.
</P>
<P>
Banks were leading the downward spiral today, as investors took
advantage of a strong performance in non-miners over the past
three months.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank, a major share represented in the SPI
(share price index) contract, was down 53 cents to 21.22
Australian dollars, Commonwealth was seven weaker at 17.04
Australian dollars and ANZ was 6.3 cents lower at 11.28 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Westpac bank finished two cents stronger at 8.70
Australian dollars, leading the market by volume of turnover as
investors awaited the pricing on AMP's offer of Westpac securities
to US retail investors, due later today.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's global media company News Corp dipped 7.3
cents to 7.077 Australian dollars, while the preferred shares in
the group slipped ten to 6.11 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the resources shares, blue chip BHP dropped 12 cents to
16.08 Australian dollars, after the diversified miner this morning
announced a wide-ranging management restructure.
</P>
<P>
The gold index defied the broader index, lifting 2.3 percent,
or 28.6 points to 1,298.3.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold was at 328.25 US dollars an ounce in late
Sydney trading today, up from 326.90 US dollars in Sydney late
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 416.16 million shares worth 1.178 billion
Australian dollars (848.16 million US dollars), with rises of 598
outnumbering falls of 547.  
</P>
</TEXT>
