<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Regrets over Taliban's Detention of European Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Head of the U.N. Special
Mission for Afghanistan Norbert Holl today expressed "deep regret"
over the detention of a European commissioner by the Islamic
Taliban militia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
European commissioner for humanitarian aid Emma Bonino and her
entourage, who were on a two-day visit to Afghanistan, were
reportedly detained late Monday by the Taliban authorities for
over three hours for taking pictures of women.
</P>
<P>
The incident is "jeopardizing a personality enjoying diplomatic
immunity and representing the European Union," said Holl, who held
talks with Bonino upon her arrival here from Kabul Monday evening,
in a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
"Bonino came to Afghanistan on purely humanitarian grounds in
order to collect first-hand information on the economic, social
and human rights situation in Afghanistan, including the situation
of women," Holl said.
</P>
<P>
"The temporary arrest of Ms. Bonino and the treatment which she
had to endure has unfortunately complicated the relationship
between the Taliban authorities and the European Community."
</P>
<P>
It may be noteworthy that the European Community and its member
states are the largest donor to Afghanistan, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who now control two thirds of Afghanistan's
territory and the capital of Kabul, have vowed to impose a strict
Islamic law in the war-torn country. In areas under Taliban
control both photography and filming of "living creatures" is
strictly banned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
