<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cable Pact Signed to Better Telecom Service in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A total of 14 countries have
signed the memorandum of understanding for "Africa One" submarine
cable network for direct telephone ties among African countries.
</P>
<P>
The project, estimated to cost three billion U.S. dollars,
will provide direct telecommunications interconnection between
African countries instead of the present system of routing
African telephone traffic through London and Paris.
</P>
<P>
The routing through Europe, according to the International
Telecommunication Union (ITU), costs the region 400 million
dollars annually, the Daily Champion reported today.
</P>
<P>
The cable link would be one of the several infrastructure
building blocks along with satellite systems and terrestrial
networks that are planned for building the global information
infrastructure of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"Africa One" coordination committee is made up of Nigeria,
Cameroun, Cote d'Ivoire, Kenya, South Africa, Tunisia and
Zimbabwe, representing the continent's five sub-regions, is
working on reaching a target of 20 to 25 signatories, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Other members of the coordination committee include the
proponents of the project, At&AMP;t Submarine Systems Inc., the
African Development Bank, the Pan-African Telecommunications
Union and the regional African Satellite Communication
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by Ahmed Laouyane, Director of Telephone
Development Bureau at the ITU headquarters in Geneva, also
reviewed the status of business cases and financial plans of
various countries with a view to identifying those that may need
soft loans to participate in the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
