<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Relations Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
expressed the hope today that China and Japan will further deepen
cooperation and raise bilateral relations to a higher plateau.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang told a group of high-ranking Japanese leaders,
economists and celebrities that Sino-Japanese ties have witnessed
remarkable progress over the past 25 years since the two nations
normalized ties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang extended a welcome to the Japanese delegation, led by
former Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
</P>
<P>
He noted that progress in bilateral relations has been
resultant from joint efforts of both countries which should be
treasured.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Jiang said, Sino-Japanese cooperation is important to
the development of Asia Pacific Region, and added that said
relations are in the fundamental interests of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The president expressed great respect for all people of both
countries who have made contributions to Sino-Japanese friendship.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope that the older generations in both countries
will educate and guide younger generations to carry Sino-Japanese
friendship into the next century," Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita echoed President Jiang's remarks by saying that
senior statesmen should make every effort to educate the young
people and ensure that Sino-Japanese is passed on from one
generation to another.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita offered congratulations on the success of the 15th
National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party and Jiang's
reelection as general-secretary.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese delegation also includes Yoshio Sakurauchi,
chairman of the Japanese Association for the Promotion of
International Trade and former parliament leader, and Gaishi
Hiraiwa, honorary president of the Federation of Economic
Organizations. 
</P>
