<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Considers Doha Summit Chance for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has said it
considered the fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
economic summit a chance to save the stalled Middle East peace
process, the Omani news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali told the news
agency during his visit to Oman that the forthcoming conference
due on November 16-18 in Qatar should be treated as an
opportunity to solve political differences between the Arabs and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Majali also stressed that his country will take part in the
summit which has been opposed by some Arab countries because of
an expected Israeli participation.
</P>
<P>
Majali arrived in the Omani capital of Muscat Saturday for a
three-day official visit to discuss economic cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, he met with Qatari senior officials and
discussed with them the MENA conference, which has divided the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinian National Authority have
announced their boycott of the conference in protest against the
deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace talks. Syria and Lebanon had
boycotted all the previous three conferences.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia also favored a
boycott, saying that they would not appear at the conference
unless major achievements are made in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, most of other Arab states adopt a wait-and-see stand
toward the conference. Qatari officials said they have not received
any refusal from these countries.
</P>
<P>
The controversial conference to include Arab states, Israel
and their partners in the industrialized world was launched in
1994. Its last session was held in Cairo last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
