<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows to Continue Settlement Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said today that despite the announced
resumption of the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, Israel will
continue building settlements at the stage.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during a ceremony in his office on the
sale of Bank Hapoalim, Netanyahu said that Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) had only agreed to discuss
the concept of "time-out" of Israel's settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's tough comments came one day after U.S. secretary
of State Madeleine Albright announced in New York that Israel and
the PNA agreed to resume peace talks to break the six-month
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's strong remarks apparently dampened the
newly emerging optimism about the peace process, which both
sides have just agreed to resume after a six-month freeze.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu stressed the need for the PNA to continue
its fight against terror, adding there could be no real peace
talks otherwise.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to discuss the concept of time-out, and each
side has of course its own views. I think the important thing is
that we have argued for a long time that peace and terror cannot
coexist," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
"We have been insisting that our Palestinian partners fight
terrorism, I think that is the principal framework of the
agreement that was reached yesterday. If they fight terror, we
will continue with the peace (process), if they don't, we won't
continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of peace talks was announced after the
U.S.-brokered talks between Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
and PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen). The two sides are
expected to resume the talks on implementing the interim
agreements on October 6.
</P>
<P>
This was the first breakthrough since the July 30 Mahane
Yehuda twin suicide bombings and the September 4 Ben Yehuda
triple bombings in Jerusalem, in which 25 people were killed and
over 300 other wounded.
</P>
<P>
The wave of terror attacks, carried out by the anti-Israeli
militant group Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), aggravated the
already tense situation between the two sides which was caused by
Israel's building of the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem in
March.
</P>
<P>
Abbas said in New York that while the PNA agreed to resume
cooperations in all fields including fighting terrorism with
Israel, it thought that Israel must refrain from taking
unilateral steps, including the closure of Palestinian self-rule
areas, settlement activities, land confiscation and demolition of
Arab houses.
</P>
<P>
In her comments on Netanyahu's statements, PNA Minister of
Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi said that the peace negotiations
could not continue unless Israel stops all building
settlements. "This is the bottom line as far as all Palestinians
are concerned," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
