<HEADLINE> China State Sector Reform to Make Giant Strides: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese minister in
charge of State Economic and Trade Commission Wang Zhongyu said
here today that the on-going state sector reform will
advance by leaps and bounds.
</P>
<P>
Wang, the sole foreign guest to take the floor at the opening
ceremony of the 11th International Industrial Conference, is
heading a Chinese delegation of 10 major state sector leaders for
the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, heads of more than 400 large enterprises from
over 60 countries are scheduled to explore the trends, strategy
and countermoves of the economy globalization.
</P>
<P>
Wang introduced that at the just-ended 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China, President Jiang Zemin expounded the
theory of the socialist market economy, indicating new development
of the theory.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the minister said, China will give state sector
strategic reorganization, aiming to create some major enterprises
with competition beyond region, industry and ownership.
</P>
<P>
China henceforth will speed up the reforms of infrastructure
fields like resources and transportation, and open the finance,
trade and service areas gradually, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
China will also amplify the foreign-oriented legislations to
promote the transparency of the foreign trade system, in a bid to
create favourable conditions for foreign investors participating
in the Chinese market competition, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
The minister's statements received warm welcome from the
participants of the conference.
</P>
<P>
The International Industrial Conference, a gathering of
high-ranking leaders of the global industrial enterprises
initiated in 1957, was held every four years in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
