<HEADLINE> UAE Puts Ceiling on Wedding Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Cabinet of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) has approved a draft law putting a ceiling on
wedding expenses in the Gulf country, official newspaper Emirates
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The draft law, which sets dowries at a maximum of 20,000
dirhams (some 5,500 U.S. dollars) and limiting wedding parties to
one day, is aimed at curbing soaring wedding expenses which have
become a heavy burden to the UAE's youth.
</P>
<P>
The draft law which also sets a 30,000 dirhams (about 8,200
dollars) limit on divorce compensation is part of the
government's effort to promote marriage among its nationals.
</P>
<P>
Wedding expenses in the UAE averaged at 100,000 dirhams (about
27,000 dollars) and wedding parties usually last for days. The
high wedding cost forced many local men to take foreign women as
brides.
</P>
<P>
UAE officials worry that the native population will decline
further if UEA men continue to marry foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The natives only constitute one quarter of the country's 2.4
million population as the rest are expatriate workers mostly from
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The government has set up a marriage fund in 1992 to help
local youth who could not afford to marry.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the Cabinet approved the draft law in
line with instructions of UAE's President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan
al-Nahyan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Smoke to Clear Out From Philippine Skies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Smoke coming from Indonesia's
forest fires is expected to clear out from the southern
Philippines in two to three weeks with the entry of the
northeasterly winds, the Philippine News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Environment and Natural Resources Secretary
Victor Ramos as saying Monday that the visibility situation in the
southern Philippines was "improving."
</P>
<P>
There will be change in the direction of winds as the
northeasterly winds will start to blow in three days' time,
replacing the existing southwesterly winds, according to Victor
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Atmospheric Geophysical and Astronomical
Services Administration (PAGASA) blamed the southwesterly winds
for bringing the heavy smoke from the raging forest fires in
Indonesia into the Philippine shores.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason to worry in the longer-term due to the
forthcoming prevalence of the northeasterly winds," Victor Ramos
said.
</P>
<P>
The southeasterly winds will blow the bulk of the smoke from
Indonesia instead towards the Malaysian Peninsula and adjacent
areas for the next two to three days, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to PAGASA's observation reports, there was a
short-lived improvement Monday in the horizontal visibility to
about 10 kilometers in the southern Philippine provinces of
Palawan and Zamboanga.
</P>
<P>
But Palawan is now back again to a low visibility situation,
showing a clear range of only four kilometers, while in Zamboanga,
visibility is reduced to five kilometers.
</P>
<P>
But the visibility condition over the rest of the southern
Philippines has already normalized to greater than 10 kilometers.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
