<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jews Continue to Be Israeli Majority : Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Jews will stay the
majority in Israel for the foreseeable future due to continued
immigration and high birth rates in certain Jewish sectors,
according to newly-released government statistics.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 State Statistical Abstract issued Monday indicated
that the country's Jewish majority would be guaranteed for at
least 20 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Israel's population increased by 140,000, of whom
88,000 were Jews. Some 71,000 new Jewish immigrants arrived in
Israel last year, including 59,000 from former Soviet states.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli current population totals 5,863,000, of whom 80.2
percent are Jewish, 14.9 percent Muslims, 3.2 percent Christians,
and 1.7 percent Druse.
</P>
<P>
Although immigration remained one of main factors contributing
to the population increase in Israel, the number of immigrants
continued the decline since the 1991 peak, as 5,000 fewer
immigrants arriving in Israel last year compared to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The number of children born in Israel rose 4 percent in
1996 from 1995 to 121,300, representing 21.3 births per 1,000
people. Jewish women gave births to 83,700 children, or 69
percent of the new births last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Current-Account Shortfall Down Sharply in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Boosted by strong exports, the
current-account shortfall of South Korea narrowed sharply to 714
million U.S. dollars in August from the 3.6 billion dollars
registered a year ago, said the Bank of Korea (BOK).
</P>
<P>
Following a continuous double-digit export growth in July and
August as well as the dropping import in August, the cumulative
deficit for the first eight months this year fell to 11.83 billion
dollars from last year's 15.77 billion dollars .
</P>
<P>
"If this trend continues, the nation's current account
shortfall is expected to reach about 14 billion U.S. dollars in
1997, falling below the central bank's earlier forecast of 17
billion dollars for the year," said Paeng Dong-joon, a BOK
manager in charge of research.
</P>
<P>
After hitting a record-high deficit of 3 billion dollars in
January, the nation's current-account shortfall dropped for five
consecutive months to 241 million in June. The red-ink figure
soared again to 977 million in July.
</P>
<P>
The weakening South Korean won against the U.S. dollar and
the business boom in the United States and Europe had caused the
nation's export surge, said the BOK official.
</P>
<P>
In August, South Korea enjoyed a 116 million dollars surplus
in its trade balance, a turnabout from the 310 million dollars
deficit in July, making the trade deficit for the first eight
months of the year amount to 6.26 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the shortfall in the invisible trade balance rose from
629 million dollars in July to 727 million dollars in August
because of the enormous amounts of payments related to overseas
travel by South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Korea's foreign-exchange holdings amounted to
31.1 billion dollars at the end of August, down 2.5 billion from
the previous month, the central bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
