<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Puts National Anthem in Film Version </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The shortest film ever made
in China premiered Monday, giving viewers a panoramic view of the
rising and falling Great Wall, the flowing Yellow River, a ship at
sea and a soaring rocket, with the Chinese National Anthem in the
background -- all in 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Produced by the Beijing Forbidden City Film Co., it is the
country's first film version of the National Anthem of the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
"China needs such a film version of the national anthem to
cater to grand ceremonies, important meetings, sport events and
Chinese embassies and consulates abroad," said Zhang Heping,
general manager of the Forbidden City Film Co..
</P>
<P>
"The short film is also a gift for the 48th anniversary of new
China," he added.
</P>
<P>
The film has 52 shots, including a dozen selected from old
documentaries.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Radio, Film and Television
believed that the film version is bound to contribute to the
patriotic education of the public, especially children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
