<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Launches Drive to Save Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Higher Education Ministry is launching a campaign
to ensure university studies for 40,000 Palestinian students who
face financial problems.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published on today's Israeli English
newspaper The Jerusalem Post, PNA Higher Education Minister Hanan
Ashrawi said she needed to raise 5 million U.S. dollars a semester,
or 10 million dollars a year, to ensure that the students who
can not pay for the tuition will continue their studies.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing an institutional breakdown in the public and
private sectors, and the last thing we need is for students to
go out into the streets," she said, adding that she would try to
prevent students from striking to protest plans to raise the
university fees.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Palestinian students pay an average of 350 dollars
per semester, about 25 percent of the real cost, in
tuition. Student leaders and Palestinian officials have been
negotiating to prevent a steep rise in tuition.
</P>
<P>
The students claimed that they have been hurt by
deteriorating economic conditions in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, due to the consistent closures imposed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
PNA officials have pledged that university students would pay
the current rates, while new students will pay an undetermined
increase that will be counted against a rate to be set in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi maintained that she has to raise the fees, although
she would also make sure that the students can afford the
tuition. She pointed out that the PNA cannot raise funds to
maintain current tuition fees, because it has not instituted a
tax to pay for higher education and has not succeeded in
obtaining funds from donor nations.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Ashrawi is raising money from European Union
nations. She revealed that so far she had won a pledge of 1
million dollars from Holland, one tenth of what the universities
need for the new school year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakh President Talks With Russian General on Border Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Abishevich Nazarbayev met here today with General Andre Nikolayev,
the visiting Russian President of the Frontierforce Commander
Committee of the Commonwealth of Independent State and Director
of the Federal Border Service, on Kazakh-Russian bilateral
relations and border issues.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev told the press after the meeting that the border
defence sectors of the two countries are prepared to draft accords
on their border and border defence in a bid to ascertain the
legal status of their common borders.
</P>
<P>
Law breakers are currently committing activities such as
smuggling and drug trafficking between the countries, which have
greatly harmed the border security and economic development of the
two countries, Nazarbayev said.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Nikolayev noted Russia and Kazakhstan have decided
to take joint steps to solidify border security by cracking down
on all the illegal activities so as to safeguard the interests of
the two countries and their peoples.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking from Kazakhstan to Russia and then to Europe
through the Central Asian countries is very rampant, and to
counter it, countries concerned are trying to co-ordinate their
actions, Nikolayev added.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day working visit here, Nikolayev also met with
Kazakh defence minister Mukhtar Kapashevich Altynbayev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
