<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Shortage Forces Liberians for Substitutes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Acute shortage of rice, the
staple food of Liberians, has forced the rural people in the
country to look for other substitutes which are few available.
</P>
<P>
The people in some of Liberia's rural areas, particularly
those bordering Cote d'Ivoire, have the only choice to eat
cassava, a plant with tuberous roots, the British Broadcasting
Corporation reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the heavy reliance of cassava, farmers were
exposed to the current crisis and now selling vegetables at
inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
In some towns, the deplorable road conditions make transport
difficult, and in the remote areas the dilapidated pick-ups,
which are the only means of transportation, take days before
reaching the markets.
</P>
<P>
Residents there have to storm the markets in the early hours
of the day just to grumble for the limited supply of cassava.
</P>
<P>
Food shortage in these areas has something to do with the
return of thousands of refugees from neighboring countries#,the
report said.
</P>
<P>
More than 700,000 Liberians fled the country during the seven
years of civil war launched by Charles Taylor, who became the
president of the country last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
