<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Panel to Probe PNA Corruption: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A new committee headed by
Speaker of the Palestinian Council Abu Ala is to be formed to
investigate the alleged corruption within the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israel's English daily Jerusalem Post reported today that the
panel would include PNA Justice Minister Freih Abu Medein,
Attorney-General Fayez Abu Rahme and several appointments to be
made by PNA President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Palestinian sources as saying that Arafat is
encouraging the investigation as part of his drive to demonstrate
to Palestinians that he wants to root out official corruption.
</P>
<P>
A report by PNA auditing office claiming that 326 million
U.S. dollars of public funds, or 40 percent of PNA budget, were
misused or wasted in 1995 by PNA ministers, created a political
uproar within the PNA.
</P>
<P>
On July 31, the Palestinian Council voted to give Arafat one
month to dissolve his Cabinet and appoint a new one. It also
recommended bringing two ministers, Planning and International
Cooperation Minister Nabil Sha'ath and Civilian Affairs Minister
Jamil Tarifi, to trial for corruption.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has since come under increased pressure from the
Palestinian public and international donors to take actions
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
A committee appointed by Arafat later found that although no
money had been squandered, serious financial, legal, and
administrative violations existed.
</P>
<P>
One day after the council's vote to demand the dissolution of
the whole PNA Cabinet, 16 PNA ministers tendered their
resignations to Arafat, who has so far refused to accept the
resignations. The latest move taken by Abu Ala seemed to be
aimed at increasing the pressure on Arafat to take quick actions
to clear the PNA's image. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Benefits Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The fact that the Yangtze
River will be diverted in early November to allow for construction
of a gigantic dam will provide wide-ranging opportunities for both
Chinese and overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Investors will benefit from increased opportunities resulting
from the fact that the market for funding, equipment and
technology will rapidly expand along with construction of the
temporary dam.
</P>
<P>
Two parallel earth and stone cofferdams will be constructed to
block the main stream of the Yangtze, the country's longest
river. The second stage will involve the construction of the dam
and generator rooms which will cover 630,000 sq.m. between the two
cofferdams.
</P>
<P>
The second stage construction will represent the investment
peak, and the Three Gorges Dam will involve a static investment of
90.05 billion yuan, with total costs for the project expected to
hit 200 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 billion yuan in funding will be needed prior to the
year 2007, including the 35 billion yuan which will be expended
prior to the year 2003. The China Yangtze River Three Gorges
Project Development Corp. will continue to use wide-ranging
fund-raising methods to obtain overseas funding, including export
credits, selling shares and commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
Equipment purchases will reach a peak once the river is blocked
and intensified construction of the dam will require more advanced
machinery and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Equipment purchases will account for close to 33 percent of
total construction costs for the Three Gorges Dam. Some 70 percent
of equipment needed for the Three Gorges Project has been
purchases from overseas companies.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six generators, with a generating capacity of 700,000 kw
each, will be installed in the Three Gorges water control dam. On
September 2, 1997, two European conglomerates were awarded
contracts for 14 generators in early September this year, with the
remaining 12 generators to be manufactured by Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Chinese experts are currently conducting
feasibility studies about the possibility of installing an
additional six generators on the right bank of the river might
possibly offer new business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Technological cooperation and exchanges will also increase
along with rising demand for new high technology and expertise
needed to construct the dam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
