<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Finance Minister Dumped Following Trips to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea's (PNG's)
Prime Minister Bill Skate has dumped Finance Minister Roy Yaki
from the cabinet for domestic and diplomatic reasons, saying he
was deeply concerned about Yaki's recent trips to Taiwan which
might cause diplomatic problems in relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister said he was deeply concerned about Yaki's
numerous trips to Taiwan recently. This may cause diplomatic
problems in the relationship between PNG and China, as the Skate
government strongly respects the one China policy of the People's
Republic of China," said a document reaching here today from the
prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
Skate questioned the competence of Yaki's short period as
finance minister since the new government was formed in mid-July,
accusing Yaki of lagging behind in the preparation of next year's
budget, which is due to be delivered in November.
</P>
<P>
"We have always recognized China and have dealt with Taiwan on
a commercial basis only, by virtue of Taiwan's growing economic
power. This should never change PNG's current foreign policy on
China," the prime minister was quoted by the document.
</P>
<P>
"Any visit by government ministers or officials to Taiwan
should be treated as private and should only be undertaken after
prior approval has been obtained from my office," the prime
minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yaki, who was in Hong Kong attending a World Bank meeting on
Monday, was also toppled as leader of his People's Democratic
Movement (PDM) at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
He was replaced as finance minister by his colleague and former
public service minister Iairo Lasaro.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister was most critical of Yaki's recent trips to
Taiwan to allegedly discuss the sale of the government airline Air
Nuigini," the Australian Associated Press said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
