<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Focuses on State Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai No.9 Knitwear
Plant, a state-owned enterprise which manufactures the popular
brand-name underwear "Sanqiang", lost its market dominance in the
late 1980s and has faced increasingly fierce competition since the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The company's management decided that an attack strategy was
the best way to promote the enterprise. The plant assumed control
of seven debt-ridden enterprises and established the Shanghai
Sanqiang Holding Group between 1991-1996..
</P>
<P>
The merger raised the plant's economic strength and its assets
have increased 11-fold over the past six years, with sales revenue
rising 13-fold and profits 101-fold. Sanqiang is now regarded as a
model of how to reform China's state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
China currently has some 87,000 medium to large state
enterprises, many of which have failed to adapt to the market and
continue to lose money despite financial support from the
government.
</P>
<P>
Related enterprises are being reformed in accordance with
government guidelines, and tens of thousands of small enterprises
which mainly produce consumer goods will either be merged, annexed
with profitable companies or bankrupted.
</P>
<P>
Some 58 pilot cities were slated for intensive enterprise
reforms in 1996, with 1,099 state enterprises forced into
bankruptcy and an additional 1,192 involved in mergers.
</P>
<P>
All sides have benefitted in cases of mergers. Konka, a
profitable television manufacturer in Shenzhen, merged with two
loss-making television plants, one in northeast China and the
other in northwest China's Shaanxi Province. Three years later, in
1996, the Konka Group chalked up sales of over 805 million yuan,
including profits of 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Focuses on State Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's leading economists agree that the dismal economic
performance of most state enterprises can be blamed on poor
management. They point to rags-to-riches private enterpreneurs as
glowing examples of just how crucial management can be to the
success of an enterprise, and insist that a modern management
system must be formed to improve performance.
</P>
<P>
Between 1994 and June 1997, the State Council designated 100
large state enterprises as pilot ventures for introducing a modern
management system, with local governments designating an
additional 2,598 ventures for similar programs.
</P>
<P>
The system features a standard corporate management structure
with boards of directors, and incentive and restraint mechanisms
for owners, managers and laborers.
</P>
<P>
The Qinchuan Machine Tools Group, a company in Northwest
China's Shaanxi Province which led the nation's machine tools
manfacturing sector in terms of 1996 profits, has clearly
delineated ownership from management. The group's board of
directors concentrates on planning and project investments, with
managers devoting themselves to production and management.
</P>
<P>
Similar experiments are ongoing in all the pilot enterprises
and some have been granted assets management power, according to
Wang Zhongyu, Chinese minister in charge of the State Economic and
Trade Commission (SETC).
</P>
<P>
The SETC agenda calls for a number of qualified pilot
enterprises to become limited liability or joint-stock limited
companies during 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Focuses on State Enterprises (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The State Council and local governments are fully cognizant of
the fact that most state enterprises are burdened by heavy debt
and a number of enterprises have turned some debt owed to the
state into the state capital fund.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the asset liability rates of 131 enterprises
trying out the measure have dropped by an average of 2.5
percentage points," according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises whose products enjoy good sales but which lack
funds for renovation will be allowed to seek funds directly from
both domestic and international markets by listing on stock
exchanges and issuance of bonds.
</P>
<P>
Priority support will be given to trans-regional, trans-trade,
large enterprises groups with different types of ownership to
enhance their competitiveness on domestic and international
markets.
</P>
<P>
These more aggressive reform policies have begun to show
results. In the first half of this year, China's state-owned
enterprises scored a 7.2 percent increase in value-added output
from last year's same period.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, the chief economist at the State Statistics Bureau
said that sighs of state enterprises recovery first showed through
at the end of 1996, when the rate of floundering enterprises
dropped from a peak of 45.6 percent to 32 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
The trend makes Qiu optimistic over further improvement in the
performance of state enterprises, believing that with the
deepening of economic reform, more state enterprises will become
assets rather than liabilities, contributing to rather than taking
from the state coffers, and playing a front line role in China's
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
