<HEADLINE> South Korean Convicted Business Tycoons to be Pardoned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
decided today to grant special pardons to seven business tycoons
including owners of Samsung and Daewoo groups who were convicted
of bribing former President Roh Tae-woo.
</P>
<P>
The pardons, subject to the approval of President Kim
Young-sam, cover Chairman Lee Kun-hee of Samsung, Kim Woo-choong
of Daewoo, Choi Won-sok of Dong-ah, Chang Jin-ho of Jinro, Lee
Joon-yong of Daelim, Kim Joon-ki of Dongbu and Lee Kun, executive
of Daeho Construction Company.
</P>
<P>
They were sentenced to one to four-year jail terms earlier this
year with a rather long suspension while former Presidents Chun
Du-hwan and Roh Tae-woo were sentenced respectively to a whole
life and 22 years imprisonment for mutiny and taking bribes.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Young-sam was quoted as saying earlier this month
that he will release his two jailed predecessors before his term
expires next February.
</P>
<P>
The government's move today was interpreted as a way to help
revitalize the nation's sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The government today also decided to pardon 16 other business
executives who have been convicted of embezzling corporate money
or evading tax.
</P>
<P>
The special pardon bill, however, does not cover politicians
and officials involved in taking bribes from the businessmen or
arranging bribes for former presidents Chun and Roh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
