<HEADLINE> Uganda, Tanzania Hammer Common Strategy on Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 30 (Xinhua) --Chiefs from Crime
Investigation Departments (CID) of Uganda and Tanzania have
agreed on a common strategy to deal with cross-border crime,
local daily The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
The strategy was reached at a joint border security meeting
held in Masaka, southwestern Uganda over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended by police officers from both countries,
was to enable the CID chiefs to hear directly from field officers
their experiences in handling cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will help the two sides formulate
appropriate strategies to combat crime.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda were discussions on rampant armed car
robberies, smuggling, drug trafficking, cattle rustling and petty
theft.
</P>
<P>
Both Tanzania and Uganda agreed to regularly exchange
intelligence information about criminals.  
</P>
