<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Presidential Palace to Become Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The former Kuomintang (KMT)
presidential palace in Nanjing in east China's Jiangsu Province,
will soon become a museum of modern Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government offices are preparing to vacate the
complex and preparations for restoration are under way.
</P>
<P>
The palace, which features magnificent halls, gardens and and
groves, was the residence of the governor-general of Jiangsu,
Jiangxi and Anhui provinces during the Qing Dynasty (1616-1911).
</P>
<P>
Hong Xiuquan, leader of the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom
(1851-1864), made Nanjing the kingdom's capital and lived in the
palace during the Taiping Revolution, one of the largest peasant
uprisings in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The palace was the site Dr. Sun Yat-sen was sworn in as the
temporary president of the Republic of China following the
Revolution of 1911, and later became the presidential palace of
KMT government before the founding of new China in 1949. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
