<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Monks Protest Against Devolution Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 Buddhists this
morning launched a sit-down demonstration in the center of Colombo
in protest against the devolution proposals of the government.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, sitting in the vicinity of the Viharamaha
Devi Park, said "the reason of the package is to satisfy Tamil
extremists."
</P>
<P>
The placards held by the monks said, "no more talks with the
brutal LTTE terrorists" and "against the devolution package."
</P>
<P>
Some monks distributed leaflets to passersby. A large crowd of
people gathered at the venue to show their support to the monks.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was launched by the National Sangha Sabha
(National Association of Buddhists) and the National Joint
Committee, an organization of 56 associations in the country.
</P>
<P>
It started at 9:00 a.m. local time and was scheduled to end by
noon. Quite a number of policemen were deployed at the scene to
maintain order.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said it is very difficult for the government to
push through the proposals if it cannot gain support from the
Buddhists. Buddhism is quite influential in Sri Lanka's social
affairs and politics.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators were also protesting against remarks made by
Ports, Telecommunications and Media Minister Mangala Samaraweera
last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On commenting the Interim Report of the Sinhala Commission, the
minister and government spokesman said the report was "the biggest
conspiracy against the Sinhala people."
</P>
<P>
He went on to say, "The Sinhala Commission report will very
soon be consigned to the dustbin."
</P>
<P>
Piyasena Dissanayake, secretary of the National Joint
Committee, said the statement made by the minister raised doubts
as to whether his stand with regard to the Interim Report
represented the government's attitude towards the report.
</P>
<P>
He said the demonstration was launched to compel the minister
to withdraw his statement.
</P>
<P>
The Sinhala Commission, composed of 12 members, was appointed
by the National Joint Committee to examine problems that are
related to the Sinhala people.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Report, the first report of the Sinhala Commission
since it was established two years ago, has rekindled a
nation-wide political controversy by opposing the devolution
proposals of the government.
</P>
<P>
Under the devolution proposals, more autonomy would be given to
the Northern and Eastern provinces, where the Tamil rebels have
been fighting a guerrilla war for a separate state since 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
