<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are
economic news briefs from the Latin American countries over the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Banana exports from Panama fell both in volume
and value from January to August from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Panama`s National Office for Banana said overseas sales were
over 22 million boxes during the period, 8 percent fewer than that
of the same period last year. Sales fell by 10.63 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Electric power tariffs in Nicaragua will be raised
by 5 percent since October, Central Bank President Noel
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
The raise is due to the drought caused by the climatic
phenomenon known as "El Nino." Water for hydroelectrical plants
has diminished, the president said.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's trade deficit will total 4 billion
dollars in 1997, 1 billion higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
The deficit will be due to the dramatic surge in imports, said
the institute of Fiscal and Economic Studies.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit was 1.86 billion during the first seven
months. But in the same period of last year, there was a trade
surplus of 567 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's state-owned oil company Petroleos de
Venezuela (PDVSA) said in a report that an unprecedented average
of 1.64 million barrels of crude were refined in the country each
day during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The figure means a growth of 51,000 barrels a day, or 5 percent
compared with the same period of 1996, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Some 2.13 million barrels of crude and 840,000 barrels of
refined products were sold in international markets in the first
six months. The total sales were a 12 percent increase over the
same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil registered a 800 million dollar deficit
in trade with its Southern Common Market (Mercosur) partners in
the first eight months.
</P>
<P>
The deficit is 33 percent higher than that in the same period
of last year, the Ministry of Industry, Commerce and Tourisms of
Brazil reported in a release.
</P>
<P>
The negative balance came up when imports -- totaling 6.4
billion dollars -- surpassed 5.6-billion-dollar exports.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Mexican businessmen have invested 400 million
dollars in Costa Rica over the last 12 years.
</P>
<P>
There are about 100 Mexican companies in Costa Rica, 11 percent
of them big conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's investments in Costa Rica stand for 12 percent of the
total direct foreign capital inflow in that Central American
country.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's raw oil imports from Argentina
increased by 20 percent during the first eight months compared
with the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's import of Saudi Arabia oil dropped by 15 percent to
445.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- More than 600,000 tourists will visit Guatemala
this year and are likely to spend some 350 million dollars,
tourism authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 520,000 foreign visitors spent 286 million dollars
in the country.
</P>
<P>
A news release from Guatemala City said tourism, after coffee
industry, is the second largest earner of foreign currencies in
Guatemala. Annual revenues of coffee production averaged 600
million dollars in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan farms had 18 million heads of wool
cattle in July, representing a drop of 7 percent against 1996,
according to the Uruguayan Secretariat of Wool (USW).
</P>
<P>
According to USW President Leandro Gomez, production apiece
would rise from 3.9 kilograms last year to slightly above 4
kilograms this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
