<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Economy Trickling Toward Border Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The best way to escape
poverty lies not in growing crops, but in developing an "economic
forest," China's southern borders believe, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The inhabitants of Yunnan province's Jinpin and Luchun
bordering Vie Nam have gradual faith in market economy, though
they are cut off from the outside world by inefficient
transportation and communication.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1980s, farmers rushed into the mountains to plant
citronella, as it became a hot product on the international market
and its oil worth more than 12 US dollars a kilogram. They thought
the way to wealth had been found, but the price plunged to 2.1 US
dollars a kilogram. Most farmers fell into econmic plight.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, banana farmers in Luchun County had a bumper harvest,
but heavy rain had ruined the shabby roads, and they could do
nothing but allow the fruit to rot away in the field.
</P>
<P>
However, the local officials understood that the government
should act as a bridge between poor farmers and the market, and
began to help farmers map out projects according to the market's
ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
So far, large plantations of rubber trees and other tropical
fruit trees have been established throughout Jinpin and Luchun as
a result of careful market investigation. And private capital and
local finances have been invested in these projects.
</P>
<P>
The products will be delivered to big cities within and outside
Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The local government is trying their utmost to build a standard
road system and combine farmers together with corporations which
will help transport farmers' produce to market if they think it
profitable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland's Trade Deficit Reaches 9 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Poland's trade deficit in the
first seven months of this year reached 9 billion U.S. dollars, an
increase of 2.4 billion dollars over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The deficit to European Union countries accounts for 5.5
billion dollars of the total, according to the figures released by
Poland's Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Economy estimates that exports from Poland will
be 27 billion dollars while imports will be 40 billion dollars in
1997, resulting in a trade deficit of 13 billion dollars, which
far exceeds the 9.4 billion-dollar target the government set for
the year.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the Ministry of Economy said that various elements
stimulating imports have contributed to the rise in trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The elements include increased foreign investment, the
abolishment of border duties on imports and the reduction of
average tariffs from 7.45 percent to 5.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of the country's economy needs to be
propped up by the inflow of foreign capital and import of capital
goods, which accounted for 80 percent of the total imports in the
first six months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The key to curbing the rapid increase in trade deficit lies in
raising competitivity of Poland's products and their prices, the
experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
