<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Economy Earns More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's external
economy
earned "a handsome income" of 17 billion Singapore dollars, or
around 11.7 billion U.S. dollars, last year, up significantly from
the 11.7 billion Singapore dollars (about 8 billion U.S. dollars)
yielded in 1990, the Straits Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said that the income earned by the Republic from abroad
comprises earnings from capital investment, labor, and
intellectual property, namely, patent fees and royalties.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the money came from foreign assets, as income from
these investments increased to 16.9 billion Singapore dollars from
11.6 billion in 1990, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, although investment abroad by Singapore
companies had increased, the pace had not kept up with that of
Singapore-based multi-national corporations (MNCs).
</P>
<P>
Citing the result of a study by the Statistics Department, the
Straits Times report said that half of the total direct investment
was undertaken by Singapore-based MNCs, which means that MNCs
helped bring in a significant part of Singapore's overseas
earnings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
