<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Quake Toll Rises to 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The number of people who died
in Sunday's tectonic earthquake in Indonesia's South Sulawesi
province increased to 18, following the finding of two more
victims, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measuring 6.4 on the Richter scale, jolted some
districts in the province at 9:38 a.m. local time, and also
injured more than 300 others.
</P>
<P>
A total of 561 houses were damaged in addition to 51 school
buildings, 21 offices, 19 prayer houses, seven cars and three
motorcycles, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The loss is estimated at 6 billion rupiah (2 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake is located at 3.85 degrees of the
south latitude and 119.65 degrees of the east longitude at a depth
of 300 kilometers, some 54 kilometers southeast of Polewali
district.
</P>
<P>
The worst hit areas are Pinrang, Pare-pare, Sidrap and Polewali
as well as Ujungpandang, capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
The meteorology and geophysics agency in Ujungpandang detected
Monday 16 more tremors after the first quake in the neighboring
towns of Pare-pare and Sidrap, but no casualties and loss were
reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
