<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harbor in Northeast China To Issue B Shares Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Jinzhou Harbor in Northeast
China's Liaoning Province is expected to issue B shares around the
end of October and A shares next year, today's China Daily
quoted the Orient Group Co., the harbor's biggest shareholder,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhou's quota of 100 million B shares has been approved by
securities authorities of the central government and the stocks
will be listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange, said officials of
Orient, which is based in Harbin, capital of northeast
Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhou Harbor opened in 1986 under State ownership and was
transformed into a joint-stock company in late 1995, when Orient
bought 30.4 percent of its ownership.
</P>
<P>
A series of efficiency-oriented reforms followed the
shareholding transformation.
</P>
<P>
Handling capacity of the harbor was raised to 4.5 million tons
by the end of last year from two million tons in 1995, with
profits soaring to 65 million yuan from 20 million yuan, according
to Orient Group Vice-President Guan Guoliang.
</P>
<P>
He said Jinzhou's listing would reflect Orient's increasing
interests in raising capital through the stock market to fund
development and expansion.
</P>
<P>
Orient was the first company in Heilongjiang to obtain the
local government's approval to issue stocks and is one of Chinese
first private companies to have a listed subsidiary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
