<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Enact Laws Against Child Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will enact stringent
laws to protect children from trafficking, repression and killing.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina made this statement
while inaugurating the Child Right Week Program in Dhaka Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The nation will enforce trial and exemplary punishment to
those who commit such crimes," the prime minister said, calling
upon all irrespective of political and party affiliation to help
introduce tough laws to put an end to the vice.
</P>
<P>
Those involved in such crimes must be given exemplary
punishment so that nobody can dare to do the same in the future,
she stressed.
</P>
<P>
She added, "We can ensure safety and security of the children
through punishing the killers under the legal provision."
</P>
<P>
It is the sacred duty of all to bring up children as worthy
citizens of the country by providing proper care, education and
health services, the prime minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
She also said that her government was working to ensure the
enrollment of 95 percent of children of age group 6 to 10 in
schools and reduce the rate of dropout by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspapers, about 200,000 children and women
of Bangladesh have been trafficked to the Middle East in the past
20 years, and the Bangladeshi government is deeply concerned over
the growing trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
