<HEADLINE> Hungary to Resolve Dam Dispute with Slovakia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime minister
Horn Gyula said today that a ruling by the world court on
Hungarian-Slovak feud over a dam on the Danube River provided
prerequisite for the two countries to reach a "mutually acceptable
solution."
</P>
<P>
Horn told the Hungarian Congress that he had sent a letter to
Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar proposing talks "in good
faith" at the end of October at the latest on how to implement the
ruling by the U.N. International Court of Justice in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
The talks could end years of wrangling between the two
countries over the giant Bos dam they agreed to jointly build on
the Danube, their border river, to generate electricity in 1977.
</P>
<P>
However, Hungary unilaterally suspended the work on its side in
1989, and abrogated the bilateral agreement, citing environmental
reasons in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia responded by modifying the original designs and
diverting the Danube water to Slovak territory to feed a power
station at Gabcikovo for its own use.
</P>
<P>
They went to the International Court in 1992. After almost five
years of investigation, the court ruled on September 25 that both
countries had violated the agreement they had signed in 1977, and
that they should pay each other damages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
