<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Steel Industry Aims For Quality, Variety (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- China plans to raise the
quality of its steel products, rather than increasing output, as
an adjustment to its goal for the metallurgical industry.
</P>
<P>
China, with 101.1 million tons of steel production last year,
became the world's top steel producer.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qi, minister of the metallurgical industry, told Xinhua
that China is going to produce roughly the same amount of steel
this year, but that it is of the quality and variety the ministry
was expecting to see in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said that China plans to improve the continuous casting
ratio -- a major indicator of the metallurgical industry's
technological level -- from 53 percent last year to 75 percent by
2000, which was already a rise of six percentage points over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that China hopes to build at least five more iron and
steel works up to international standards in the remaining years
of this century. But, he stressed, technological renovations of
the existing enterprises rather than construction of new ones will
be the chief means of upgrading China's iron and steel industry.
</P>
<P>
China has 106 iron and steel works rated as medium or
large-sized, most of which were started in the early and mid-1950s
with Soviet assistance, or earlier, as in the case of the Anshan
Iron and Steel Co. in northeast China's Liaoning Province, which
was built by the Japanese in 1917.
</P>
<P>
Only Baoshan in the south and the Tianjin Pipe Company in the
north meet international standards for technological processes,
technology and production capacity.
</P>
<P>
"To get the job done, you need money and the best kind of
technology and you have to make proper arrangements for
re-employment of those workers laid off as a result of the
technological upgrading," Liu said. "The job is tough and
time-consuming, but given the specific conditions of China, that
is the only alternative."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Steel Industry Aims For Quality, Variety (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The industry will open up more opportunities for foreign
investors, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Five iron and steel heavyweights, including Panzhihua Iron and
Steel Co. based in Sichuan Province, Anshan Iron and Steel Co. and
Daye Iron and Steel Co. based in Hubei Province, are getting
quoted either on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, or have issued B
shares on the domestic stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Yang Xiaoning, deputy director of the ministry's Economic
Research and Development Center, said that the ministry is
launching a series of schemes to promote quality control, increase
the variety of products, and encourage use of technology that is
cost and energy effective while environmentally friendly.
</P>
<P>
"The overall plan is to ensure that 90 percent of China's
rolled steel meets international standards by 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the last couple of years have witnessed a constant
increase in the production of quality steel products, "such
products are still in limited quantity relative to the
ever-expanding demand on the domestic market," the expert noted.
</P>
<P>
He cited a range of products now in acutely short supply on the
domestic market: galvanized sheets, tin plate, cold-rolled
sheeting, cold-rolled silicon sheeting, oil pipes, as well as
varieties specially for use in automobile, electric power,
petroleum and chemical industries.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, he said, China plans to meet 95 percent of its own
needs for rolled steel; the figure is 70-80 percent for
technology-intensive, high value-added steel products. Besides,
the country will become 80 percent self-sufficient in automobile
sheeting and 75 percent in oil pipes.
</P>
<P>
This year, Chinese enterprises are producing an extra two
million tons of steel good enough to replace imports, including
cold-rolled steel, oil pipes, container sheets and sheets for
shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai-based Baoshan Iron and Steel Company,
technologically one of the best in China, is striving to build up
over the next few years an additional annual production capacity
of two to three million tons of sheets used in the country's
automobile industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yang said, import of steel products will remain
important at least in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China is only 60 percent self-sufficient in
galvanized sheeting and 30 percent self-sufficient in tin plate.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country imported 16 million tons of steel
products, 15 percent more than in 1995. It exported five million
to six million tons of steel, which was insignificant compared
with its huge output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
