<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Visits Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen will start a week-long trip to Europe on Wednesday
to discuss issues of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
with his European counterparts, the Pentagon announced today.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is to attend an informal meeting of NATO defense
ministers in Maastricht, the Netherlands, on Wednesday and Thursday
to discuss "current NATO issues," the Pentagon announced in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Cohen will travel to Sofia, Bulgaria. There,
he will attend the Southeastern European Defense Ministerial and
also meet with Bulgarian officials.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Cohen, who strongly insists that the U.S. pull out
all its troops of Bosnia, will travel to Tuzla to lunch with U.S.
troops stationed there.
</P>
<P>
He will also hold talks with General Wesley Clark, the head of
U.S. and NATO forces in Europe, and other U.S. military commanders
posted with the allied peacekeeping mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Cohen then will pay a three-day visit to Paris, where he will
visit a French air base and hold talks with French defense
officials.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon sources said that he is expected to reject France's
demand that the U.S. gives the control of NATO's southern flank
command to a European.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to return to Washington on October 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
