<HEADLINE> Balkan Countries to Discuss Suppression of Organized Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the three Balkan
countries will hold a summit meeting in Bulgaria on October 3 to
discuss the cracking down of organized crimes, Bulgarian President
Peter Stoyanov said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before his departure for Germany,
Stoyanov said that he will meet his Romanian and Turkish
counterparts Emil Constantinescu and Syuleiman Demirel in
Bulgaria's Black Sea capital Varna.
</P>
<P>
The key topic of the Varna summit will be coordination of
actions among the Balkan states for the suppression of organized
crimes, Stoyanov said.
</P>
<P>
He said that they will also discuss the practical application
of the infrastructure projects which pass the territories of the
three Balkan states.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the presidents of Romania and Bulgaria will
probably ask Turkey's support for the association of the two
Balkan nations into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO),
according to sources here.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and Romania are among the official candidates for full
membership in the NATO. 
</P>
