<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Estonia Seek Closer Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TALLINN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Chairman of the Chinese
National People's Congress Standing Committee Tomur Dawamat said
here today that China hopes to further its relations with Estonia
in all respects.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a meeting with Estonian Deputy
Undersecretary of the Foreign Ministry Mart Laanemae.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Estonian relations have developed smoothly since
Estonia's independence in 1991 and the exchange of visits by
leaders of the two countries has further promoted the relations,
said Tomur, who arrived here Sunday night on a five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Tomur said he believed his visit will push forward the
cooperative and friendly ties between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Laanemae greeted Tomur over the forthcoming 48th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
He said Estonia and China have many in common and there exists
vast potential for cooperation in the economic and other fields
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Tomur met with Tonne Kelam, vice-president of
the Estonian parliament and had talks with Tiit Made, chairman of
the Economic Committee of the Estonian parliament.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, both sides indicated that the Estonian
parliament and the Chinese National People's Congress should
strengthen exchanges so that economic cooperation between the two
countries could be further carried out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
