<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah Hits Another Low, Stocks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rupiah fell
Monday to a new historic low of 3,220 against the U.S. dollar and
the stock prices trailed down, dealers and brokers said today.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers attributed the rupiah's fall to a combination
of improving rupiah liquidity, increasing dollar demand and a
sharp fall in other regional currencies, especially the Malaysian
ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah dropped to a new low of 3,320 in the afternoon,
compared with the day's opening of 3,125/3,235 and Friday's close
of 3,100/3,122. It closed at 3,215/3,220 Monday.
</P>
<P>
One state bank chief dealer said many local corporate companies
entered the market Monday looking for dollar. As no local players
sold dollar, overseas operators could easily push down the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jakarta Stock Exchange composite index, the main
indicator of the local share prices, fell 0.7 percent or 3.682
points to close at 546.238. Total turnover was 185.23 million
shares worth 83.17 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Stockbrokers said the market was dull Monday, with most
investors staying on the sidelines following the rupiah's collapse
and failed expectation on rates cut.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said Monday that the
government will avoid making the Indonesian currency either too
strong or too weak against the U.S. dollar in helping the rupiah
reach a new equilibrium in the wake of the recent currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
He told a meeting here that nobody could now tell at which
level the rupiah's value would settle down.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and more than 25 percent since January this year following
offshore speculative attacks on the currency and a rush by local
companies to hedge their foreign borrowings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US House Approves Stop-gap Bill For New Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives approved today a temporary spending bill that will
keep funding for federal departments and agencies, preventing
another government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
The House approved the stop-gap measure with a vote of 355-57
which was widely expected. And the U.S. Senate was preparing to
match the House's action Tuesday, hours before the midnight
deadline when the current budget expires.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which was approved one day before the new fiscal year
begins on October 1, will keep U.S. government departments and
agencies working at current levels through October 23. They would
lose their funding and be forced to close temporarily without the
stop-gap bill.
</P>
<P>
So far, the U.S. House and Senate have agreed on legislation
that outlines spending on military construction projects, keeps
money flowing to Congress and its legislative functions, and a
massive measure providing 248 billion dollars for the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
Even if President Bill Clinton signed all three bills, that
would leave a dozen federal departments and scores of agencies,
without money cash, unless there is temporary funding.
</P>
<P>
Neither side, especially Republican leaders, wants a repeat of
the tortuous partial government shutdowns during a fiscal showdown
two years ago. The shutdowns had resulted in strong public rage
which mostly directed at the Republicans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
