<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Cracks Down on Unhygienic Preserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is stepping up
crackdown on preserves which contain harmful ingredients.
</P>
<P>
According to today's local newspaper The New Light of Myanmar,
19 more brands of locally produced preserves have been listed by
the Ministry of Health as containing chemical dyes or bacteria
which cause stomach disorders and are harmful to the consumers.
</P>
<P>
Producers of the preserves are warned to cease production.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, nine other brands of the preserves were
blacklisted by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the authorities have also enhanced crackdown on
expired food and medicines on sale in the markets since last
month, banning 14 brands of traditional drugs and 26 local and
foreign brands of purified bottled water for public consumption in
the country for their failure to meet the required standard after
examination.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar enacted the National Food Law in March this year,
forming a special Food and Drug Authority in its bid to enable the
public to consume food of genuine quality, free from danger and
hygienic problem, and to control and regulate the production,
import, export, storage, distribution and sale of food
systematically.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
