<HEADLINE> New US 50-Dollar Bills to Circulate Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The redesigned 50-dollar
bill will circulate on schedule starting from October 27 despite a
tiny printing flaw, the U.S. Treasury Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The new 50-dollar bill features an off-center, enlarged
portrait of U.S. Grant, the 18th U.S. president, on the front and
an updated engraving of the U.S. Capitol on the back.
</P>
<P>
It also has a large high-contrast numeral on the back, designed
to make the bill easier to identify for older people and others
with poor vision.
</P>
<P>
The 50-dollar bill is also packed with features designed to
thwart counterfeiters. These include a watermark to the right of
the portrait, an embedded polymer security thread that glows
yellow in ultraviolet light, and color-shifting ink in the numeral
in the lower right hand corner of the bill's front.
</P>
<P>
After printing 150 million bills between late May and late
August, the U.S. government discovered that about 20 percent,
about 30 million dollars, had a small break in the lines around
the portrait.
</P>
<P>
The flawed notes are under seal and a determination about
whether they can circulate will be made later. In the meantime,
the Treasury Department said enough flawless notes will be
delivered to Federal Reserve banks around the country to begin
distribution on October 27.
</P>
<P>
The introduction follows the debut of the redesigned 100-dollar
note last year. A new 20-dollar bill is also expected next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestine to Resume Interim Committee Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Palestine agreed
here today to resume negotiations in the interim committees with
the objective of setting a mutually agreed target date for
high-level peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a trilateral meeting between U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and PLO negotiator Abu Mazen in a downtown hotel here
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Terming the meeting as "productive," Albright told a press
conference, "Clearly we've come together with a common purpose and
aim -- to continue our efforts to achieve an Israeli-Palestinian
peace based on the principles agreed to at Madrid and in the Oslo
Accords" reached in 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
"We all agreed that it is essential to re-energize the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations and to create the kind of
environment necessary for those negotiations to succeed," said
Albright, who met with Levy before the three-party talks.
</P>
<P>
These negotiations will begin the week of October 6 with a
meeting of the Joint Liaison Committee chaired by Levy and Abu
Mazen, she said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will return to Washington
for the week of October 13 to work together with U.S.
participation on the elements of getting the overall peace process
back on the track, she added.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in the Mideast has been on the hold for about
six months since Israel began Jewish housing expansion in East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Israel has most recently expressed its willingness to resume
contacts with Palestine as it felt that the Palestinian Authority
had taken "preliminary steps in combating terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Albright called today's meeting a "medium step" towards
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and said "the road ahead is not an
easy one." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
