<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Legislators Back Campaign Finance Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A group of former U.S.
Congress members are urging their ex-colleagues to overhaul
campaign finance rules.
</P>
<P>
Led by prominent Republicans who recently retired, 81 former
lawmakers today issued a statement pushing for fund-raising
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The 33 Republicans and 48 Democrats sought a ban on "soft
money" -- largely unregulated donations that are supposed to be
used only for generic party activities, but were obviously used to
help candidates during the last election cycle.
</P>
<P>
They argue that such a ban and other curbs would "assure the
American public that the nation's campaign finance system honors
our nation's ideals."
</P>
<P>
The issue of campaign funding, and how both parties broke the
rules in last year's elections, has become a focus of the
controversies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
Republicans have been accusing Democrats of misdeeds in last
elections, while they themselves are also facing similar
allegations. Republican leaders have made clear their displeasure
with a proposed soft-money ban.
</P>
<P>
Republicans routinely outpace Democrats in fund raising, soft
money in particular. Statistics from the Federal Elections
Commission show that in the first half of this year, Republicans
have raised more than three dollars in soft money to every two
collected by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Senate Republican leader Trent Lott opposes the soft-money ban
in a compromise measure drafted by Senators John McCain, a
Republican of Arizona, and Russell Feingold, a Democrat of
Wisconsin. The head of the National Republican Senatorial Campaign
Committee, Kentucky Republican Senator Mitch McConnell, has vowed
to kill the measure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
