<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jospin Raps US for Imposing Its Own Law on World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin today severely criticized the United States for imposing
its own law upon other countries and warned Washington against
interfering in cooperation between the French oil group Total and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
"The American laws apply themselves in the United States, they
are not applied in France," said Jospin on TF1 television channel
this evening in a clear reaction to the U.S. announcement that it
will consider imposing sanctions upon Total for signing a 2
billion U.S. dollar contract with Iran to develop an offshore gas
field in the Persian (Arab) Gulf.
</P>
<P>
With a domestic law -- the d'Amato law -- in force, the United
States bans any country from dealing more than 40 million U.S.
dollars in oil and the hydrocarbon sector with Iran and Libya, two
countries Washington accused of supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"The whole of the European Economic Community is united in
position which is ours because nobody accepts the idea that the
United States could impose its law on a global scale," said
Jospin.
</P>
<P>
He said that the American laws adopted by the U.S. Congress for
Americans should not be addressed to Frenchmen or French
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"The private French or foreign enterprises decide freely on
their investment. They are not controlled by us and this is the
case of Total," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
He said that the political situation is turning for the better
in Iran, and French companies don't want to be the last to enter
its oil market.
</P>
<P>
"The famous d'Amato law is perhaps valid for the Americans, but
the United Nations has not decided to put an embargo upon Iran as,
for example, it has done it for Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a spokesman of the European
Commission in Brussels said today that any application by the
United States of the d'Amato law against Total will be "illegal
and unacceptable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970930.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Blames Israel for Crisis in Mideast Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa today blamed Israel for the current crisis in
the Middle East peace process and urged Israel to change its
positions for the benefits of the peoples in the region.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remarks in an address to the general debate of
the United Nations General Assembly as the United States was
stepping up its efforts for the resumption of Israeli-Palestinian
peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy, eight Arab ministers and Palestinian
negotiator Mahmoud Adbas (Abu Mezen) earlier in the day in New
York in preparations for the peace talks between Israelis and
Palestinians later today.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister claimed that Israel's settlements
policy in the occupied Arab territory was "making a mockery of
legal accords" and "pushing things to confrontation."
</P>
<P>
"The most apparent manifestation of this crisis is that the
concept, consequences and bases of the peace drive are being
completely blown off and squandered," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Trust has been replaced by doubt," Moussa stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, Levy defended Israel's policies during the same debate
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that his government welcomed U.S. efforts to revive
the stalemated peace process with the Palestinians but was no
longer willing to "pay the bloody price" in the name of peace.
</P>
<P>
He alleged that the current crisis resulted from mounting
violence in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
