<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The U.N. Security Council Committee for Monitoring
Sanctions on Iraq has approved a contract signed by the Egyptian
Food Products Holding Company with Iraq, the Middle East News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, the company will supply 8 million
U.S. dollars of vegetable oil to Iraq, said Aouni Hashem, director
of the Egyptian Trade Center in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The company concluded on September 5 four contracts with Iraq
on Egypt's supplying to Iraq vegetable oil, soap and detergents
with a total value of 19.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The shareholders of Solidere, Lebanon's largest and
most profitable company, have decided to allow foreigners to buy
and own its stock, local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The company lifted the nationality restriction but kept a ten
percent limit on ownership by a single owner.
</P>
<P>
But a Solidere official said that the move still requires
approval from the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri had said his cabinet would approve
Solidere's plan, the official said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Two leading Lebanese banks are planning to raise 175
million U.S. dollars on the international capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Fransabank, the country's second most profitable bank, will
issue 100 million U.S. dollars of five-year Euro bond. Audi
bank, the third largest, plans to raise 75 million dollars through
a ten-year subordinated loan.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon will offer a 500-million-U.S. dollar tender
to switch the source of power generation at the end of this year,
local press reported.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to protect the country's environment
from pollution by replacing regular fuel of oil with liquefied
natural gas as the sole energy for power plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
