<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Criticizes Algerian Gov't, Condemns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin today criticized the Algerian government for using violence
in order to put down a Muslim insurrection.
</P>
<P>
He also condemned what he called the "scandalous violence" of
Islamic extremists in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for a French prime minister to openly
criticize the Algerian government for years. France has maintained
a low-profile policy toward Algeria, although it is the biggest
economic supporter of Algeria, providing Algiers with 1 billion
U.S. dollars of subsidized loans each year.
</P>
<P>
"In the case of Algeria, the very great difficulty is that we
don't know what is really going on in Algeria.... We see well a
hideous terror, a violence which develops against the people, but
it is extremely difficult to identify what is going on," said
Jospin during an evening interview with the TF1 television
channel.
</P>
<P>
He said that in Algeria, there is "fanatical and violent
opposition which is fighting against a power which itself uses a
certain way of violence and the force of state."
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we should be careful (in making policy toward
Algeria)," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said last week that only
Algerians themselves can restore order and security in their
country, and that it is extremely difficult for outsiders to
interfere in the Algerian conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian extremist Armed Islamic Group (GIA) last week
threatened to launch new terrorist attacks against France because
of its support to the Algerian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
